\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. My father came from a mining family. His father had
 been a skilled miner, who was then promoted to mine supervisor, or Deputy, and then to Overman, which is, as it were, the highest supervisory level before you get to managers who needed a professional mining qualification. My father\rquote 
s brothers went into mining, and some of his sisters married miners. My father, himself, worked all his life as a clerk at a colliery in the next village \endash 
 spent 50 years in the same office as a wages clerk, and then a cost clerk. And my mother came from a rather different kind
 of family. She was one of four sisters, and two of her sisters married mineworkers, so we were, in part, a mining family. And the community that I grew up in this little village the majority of men in that village would work in the mine by the village, o
r in neighbouring mines. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So the mine was quite close? You could see the pithead from your house? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Oh yes. The house we lived in was on the edge of a ridge overlooking the Dearne Valley, and there were two mines actually in the valley, less than a mile from the house. My father worked in the neighbouring village \endash 
 the mine there. There were mines every few miles in that area. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I picture a small boy growing up just before the War, there are mines around you \'85 There are so many stories tha
t miners tell about what it\rquote s like and I just wondered whether there was anything that impinged on your early childhood/primary school years? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, I suppose the main thing was that there was a pathway, a bridle path, and then another footpath clos
e to our house, that miners would walk from the village to the mine and back again. So you saw them coming back, black-faced, and so on \endash  it\rquote 
s the kind of thing that I suppose a young child asked questions about. And then, of course, my father would talk about what was happening at the pit, and my uncles would always be talking about mines and so on. So you just grew up with the idea that that
\rquote s what work meant - working down the mine or at least in the colliery in some role or other. And visually from the 
windows in our house, you looked down this hill and saw in the valley below this enormous slag heap, and it had little tubs running along it, and then tipping at the top, so that\rquote s what I remember \endash 
 watching these things. There was the railway line in front of it which would take the coal off, mainly to Rotherham and Sheffield to the steelworks. And then there was also a by-products plant at the mine in the valley there. I\rquote 
m not sure what they did, some kind of extraction of chemicals from coal. And from time to time, if the wind was in that direction \endash  it usually was, that was the prevailing wind \endash 
 it stank, and it would discolour metal and things. We used to put pennies out and watch them go green and yellow! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 And what about the washing on the line? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Well, my mother always had to be careful about that, not to put washing out when this plant was at full blast. For some reason they called it the \'93Ottos\'94, and I never understood why it was called the \'93Ottos\'94.
 But that was something that one had to look out for. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 What, the plant? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 

\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 The plant was called the \'93Ottos\'94
, yes. It was in the mine yard. But that largely stopped during the War, I think, or shortly thereafter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Did mining carry on through the War? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Oh, absolutely. And, of course miners were exempt from military service. And, in fact we had a lot of displaced people from East Central Europe \endash  Poles and Ukrainians especially \endash  coming to work in the mines. So there was a fairly stro
ng Polish presence there. And what was quite interesting was that in these mining villages, we never had English doctors, because being a doctor in a mining area, was the bottom of the medical hierarchy. What we had when I was a small child, were Scottish
 or Northern Irish doctors who\rquote d qualified in Belfast or Glasgow, and they were a bit outside the English medical hierarchy, and then they were replaced by Polish doctors, and the one serious illness I had as a child \endash  I\rquote 
d have been about 13 or 14 \endash  I got s
carlet fever - and I was treated by a Polish doctor who was actually very resourceful. Usually you were sent off to a fever hospital if you had scarlet fever or diphtheria, and he made a break and said he would treat me at home with this new drug called 
\'93Penicillin\'94. (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So this was after the War. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 It\rquote s after the War. It\rquote s just coming in, yeah. So he was quite innovatory. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 You said, a moment ago, in passing, a fascinating little phrase. You talked about \'93mining was what work meant\'94
. Did the women in the area work, or were they all busy housewives? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
No. Very very low rate of women working. They were housewives. Very busy, because an enormous amount of washing and cleaning to do. No, women in that village worked until they married, typically. In fact, some even didn\rquote 
t work before they were married. They might be daughters helping their mothers if it was a big family and there were three or four miners in that family \endash  father and then sons - working different shifts of course. B
ecause it was all shift work, then you probably needed two or three people to do the housework and the cooking and the washing. Just the whole time, yes. Yeah. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Did you go to the local primary school? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes, local Church of England School. The village was - I suppose now you\rquote d call it a \'93bimodal village\'94
. It had been an agricultural village, rather remote agricultural village, and then the mines started being developed in that area towards the end of the 19th century and then early 20th century
, and so more housing was built for the miners. In fact, my maternal grandfather \endash  the one who figures in this book \endash 
 he was the son of a Pennine hill farmer. There were five brothers in this hill farm, and they, as it were, went east. They were farmers th
emselves. My grandfather had some training as a builder, and they moved east to Great Houghton, first of all to build houses for the miners. To begin with, they built them for the mining company, some brick houses in the neighbouring village. Then they bu
ilt stone houses in my village. Yes, stone, because that\rquote s what they were used to working with. I could show you some pictures. And these they then rented out \endash 
 they made a business of this - and they also bought land there to farm. So they fitted into the older part of the village, which was largely stone-built. Then in the inter-war years there was big housing development in the lower part of the village 
\endash  Council housing. So the village was a bit divided between, as it were, the northern end, which was th
e old agricultural end, with still three or four farms, and stone-built houses, and the lower part, with the quite big brick Council house estates. So the school I went to was a Church of England school, built in stone, at the northern end of the village,
 and then there was the Council school, a red brick building at the southern end of the village. So this was one reason when, for example, if you remember it, Dennis, Henriques and Slaughter\rquote s Ashton study [Coal Is Our Life, 1956], I thought, \'93
Don\rquote t generalise from that to mining communities. My mining community and quite a few others I know are very very different\'94
. And so this built in a very early scepticism about generalising from community studies and a failure to recognise the degree of variability....
 Yes. I mean, it did fascinate me. When I started studying history at university, I became quite interested in the history of the village. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 

\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Before we come on to history, what was your house like? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Ah! Well it was rather a different house to the rest of the village. It\rquote s a rather complicated story. My mother\rquote 
s father \endash  the builder \endash  he also became - in the inter-war years, he developed a quarry. For a while it did very well, because he exported mills
tones to Scandinavia to the forestry industry, because this was the right kind of stone for sharpening axes and things of that kind, so he became relatively prosperous in the inter-war years \endash  the thirties \endash 
 but then, unfortunately, the quarry struck a fault in the rock and could no longer produce these things. But with having the houses that he\rquote 
d built - and he got rent from this - he had a little farm that worked quite well, he was reasonably well-off, a sort of minor entrepreneur you could say. And he bu
ilt - at the end of one of the stone rows of houses that he built - he built a house for himself. Quite a nice - I can show you a photograph - stone house. And then, in one of the farms that he had, next door there was quite a big farmhouse, so the two el
d
er sisters were accommodated there. Then my mother was the third one, and I suppose [with] some idea of sibling parity, when she married he said he would build her a house on top of this ridge. All the land in this area was owned by the Fitzwilliam family
 \endash  the great aristocratic family with the enormous, biggest private house in England, Wentworth Woodhouse. And my grandfather really worked a lot as Fitzwilliam\rquote 
s mason, did a lot of the stonework on the estate, so he managed to buy this piece of land, and built a 1930s red brick house for my mother when she married. So we grew up in that, and it was very much a 1930s house. It wasn\rquote 
t big. It had a kitchen with, of course, a coal fire, two rooms downstairs, with a hallway in between, and two large bedrooms, one small bedroom upstairs, and a bathroom upstairs - it was quite an innovation. And I\rquote 
ve just been reading a book on inter-war architecture and interior decoration and this just fitted all the things \endash  parquet floor in the hall, leaded lights, bow window
s. The only thing where I think we were a bit downmarket was that in the bathroom, the loo wasn\rquote t separated \endash  that was just there in the bathroom \endash 
 but the rest of it, it was what was thought to be the kind of slightly upmarket home at that time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Where was the kitchen? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
