\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Well, you entered the house through the kitchen door. It was at the top of a road, and the front door just opened on to a garden, and then there were the fields immediately beginning. It was on the top of this ridge, there was
 a big slope down, so you entered, really, through the kitchen. Then there was a hallway, and on one side there was the living room, and then on the other side there was what was called \'93the lounge\'94
, which was only used on special occasions! (LAUGHS) All coal fires, because my father did get as part of his remuneration, a monthly ton of coal. So as I got bigger one of my jobs was always loading this coal into - it was called \'93the coal hole\'94 
\endash  there was a coal place next to the kitchen. And so a lorry would 
come every month and tip a ton of coal on the concrete in front of the house, and then we had to shovel it into the coal hole, yes! (LAUGHS) So as I got bigger, that was one of my jobs, so I learnt a bit about moving coal. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
