\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh well, not really this early experience. I got into the early work on mining in part as a result of moving over from history 
\endash  which I did my first degree in \endash 
 to sociology, because I read history at University College, London, it was a wonderful training, a very very professional school. I mean, I think I got a much better professional training as a historian there than I would 
have done at Oxford or Cambridge. And I taught history at Cambridge for a while later on. I specialised in economic and social history, and I was mainly interested in this whole, as it were, transition, first of all from so-called \'93feudalism\'94, the 
\'93manorial system\'94
, to more commercial agriculture, and then the later transition to industrialism. I got especially interested in the sociology of work. That then led to the transition that I decided to make from history to doing graduate work in sociology - mainl
y through what I read in French literature where there was more or less a unified tradition of \'93sociologie du travail\'94 and \'93histoire du travail\'94
. So that what I then became interested in, and what I wanted to do my thesis on, was the evolution of managerial systems in mining. Because one of the issues that emerged as you got larger industrial enterprises \endash 
 and this really began in Britain in the 18th century, because mines were some of the largest industrial enterprises before the beginning of the factory system \endash 
 how did you manage the workforce? And there were two main ways. One was simply sub-contracting \endash  the mine owner would simply sub-contract out the mine, or a part of the mine, to some sub-contractor - they were called \'93butties\'94
 - who would then be r
esponsible for hiring labour, and controlling labour, and paying labour, and the mine owner would simply pay the butty for the amount of coal that he produced, which the owner would then sell. So this sub-contracting, or butty system had some advantages. 
It meant that the mine owner hadn\rquote t to worry about setting up some kind of management. But it did have disadvantages as well. Partly for the mine owner, because, really, he\rquote 
d no control over the way in which the pit was worked, and it might not be worked in
 the way that would be most efficient in the long-term. And it also had major disadvantages so far as mine safety was concerned, and so from the beginning of the 19th century you got more and more State intervention in regulating the working conditions, s
afety conditions, in mines. So you did then get the development of a managerial and a supervisory system, and in some cases, in combination with what was called the \'93little butty system\'94
, where only a seam was let out, or even just a particular work area, to a sub-contractor, and that little butty system was still operating in South Yorkshire when I was a child. It went out after Nationalisation. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So did you know about it when you were a child? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
