\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh yes, because you heard people talking about this. My father\rquote 
s father was a mine Deputy, and these people were then really in this difficult position. They were paid by the mining company, but they often had to deal with these small butties \endash  the leaders of the gangs \endash  and negotiate very complicated p
ay rates, which were not only piece rates \endash  I mean, so much money for so much coal \endash 
 but then with allowances for if it was too hot, if it was too wet, if the rock was very difficult, if the seam was very narrow, and so on. So they were in a very difficult position. And then one of my mother\rquote s sisters\rquote 
 husbands had been a little butty \endash  one of the gang leaders. By the time I knew him, he\rquote d just become a day labourer in the mine because you couldn\rquote t keep up this piece rate working much beyond 40, you see \endash  it\rquote 
s too strenuous. And so this was often coming up in conversation in the family and so on. So that\rquote 
s why I wanted to work on this problem of how the management system evolved, and especially the problems of the first line supervisor as in a sense the man i
n the middle. And in particular, how the problems and the possibilities changed with the development of mining technology \endash  and that\rquote 
s what my first paper was about: the shift from this pillar-and-bord working, where the coal was mainly hand hewn with just picks - you\rquote d have picked it out - to the first kind of mechanised mining, where you have \'93long-wall\'94
 mining, where you had a machine that went along the face and cut a slice of coal, and then it had to be hand-loaded into the tubs, so it was kind of half
-and-half. And then finally you got the cutter-loader system, where the machine both cut and, by and large, loaded the coal. So all these technological changes created different managerial problems. So I worked on that, but, in fact, I never finished my P
h.D, for various reasons. When I moved to Cambridge, when I got the Prize Fellowship at King\rquote s, I was asked, \'93Well, what are you going to do now?\'94 And I said, \'93
Well, I suppose the first thing to do is to really do a final draft of my thesis for my doctorate\'94. I\rquote d published several papers, but it all was a bit falling apart, and I wasn\rquote 
t quite sure how to put it all together, and the response at King\rquote s was, \'93Why do you want a Ph.D. when you\rquote ve got a Prize Fellowship at King\rquote s? Ph.D.? A nasty Teutonic invention!\'94
 So this was music to my ears! I only realised quite a few years later, what I was missing, to bring it all together, and that was when I read a book by an American economist called Oliver Williamson, Hierarchies and Markets, which was just about this i
ssue of whether you organised things - I mean management - through a hierarchy, or a market, subcontracting. If that book had appeared, I don\rquote 
t know, ten or fifteen years earlier, I would have been able to produce a coherent thesis, because that provided a
ll the theoretical context for what I was doing. But it was too late by then. I mean, oddly enough, Williamson did draw on the work of a British economist who was at Nottingham, Ronald Coase, and [invented] transaction cost economics. He got the Nobel Pri
z
e for it some time after the War, and he did produce his first work, in Britain, I think before the War, but nobody paid much attention to it, and nobody pushed me in that direction of transaction cost economics. So anyway, that was the way in which my ac
ademic interests were related to growing up in a mining area. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
