\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Yes. Well, the first thing was, of course, that in going to the grammar school, I think I was the only one from my primary school, in that year - no, there were two, two of us went to grammar school. Of course, I found this a bit odd \endash 
 leaving my other school friends behind, and in particular there was one girl, the same year as me in the primary school, who nearly always did better than me at school. She lived in the roughest part of the village \endash 
 a row of houses by a pond, which nearly always flooded. Her father never really worked, he was the local poacher. Her mother would regularly get drunk and walk through the streets, singing, late at night. And she never had any idea - she didn\rquote t 
even take the 11+, you know, she just had to work. No question. And interestingly enough, in later life she did qualify as a school teacher. She went back, and that was marvellous, and then died, very young, of cancer, unfortunately. But that was odd, you
 
saw that some of your friends and schoolmates were going to grammar school, the others were just going to the secondary modern school for one more year really. But there was no kind of Bourdieusian culture shock in going to the grammar school, it was just
 the same sort of children, by and large. The big shock about it - well, not shock, that\rquote s too strong a word - the thing I didn\rquote 
t approve of was at school, the grammar school, you had to play rugby, whereas, of course, in the village, it was all soccer, it 
was a soccer area, and I played a lot of soccer, and so I thought that was rather peculiar. It turned out I could play rugby quite well, and I played for the school teams and so on. But no, it wasn\rquote 
t very different at all, and the main problem, for me, in the grammar school, was that because I lived so far away, and there was no public transport, I couldn\rquote 
t take part in any after school activities. So I was never as fully integrated into the school as I might have been. Then that did progressively worsen, mainly because of sport, because I played all kind of games, and in my family, on my father\rquote 
s side - I mean, cricket was a religion! And in the Yorkshire sense! And a distant cousin of mine was actually captain of Yorkshire and captain of England \endash  N.W.D. Y
ardley. Yes, a very distant cousin. My father ran the cricket team for the colliery where he worked in the next village, and they had one of the best teams in Yorkshire in the late 1940s, including two people who played for England, and one later went bac
k to play for England. So this was a great religion, and I was coached there. I didn\rquote t like playing for school, because the school pitches were very very uneven. I don\rquote 
t know whether you know anything about cricket, but I was always told you have to \'93get into line\'94
, you have to move into line, and it was very dangerous on the school pitches where the bounce was uneven. I was knocked out a couple of times, so that was one problem. Then it got worse, because in the winter, I played a lot of table-tennis, and I
 played in the Yorkshire League for Barnsley, and so on Wednesday evenings, I would be taken by taxi anywhere in Yorkshire \endash 
 it could be to Hull, to Harrogate, or wherever, and Wednesday afternoons was rugby practice for the school rugby teams, and I was a
lways worried that, you know, I might get injured, and then this taxi would come. So then it even got worse. Because it was after I\rquote 
d had scarlet fever. It was just the period when you grow very rapidly, and I had to stay in bed for a fortnight, and I just
 grew, and then convalescent for several weeks, and I just grew enormously! I grew out of all my clothes and shoes. And then the cricket season started, and I was totally uncoordinated. I was useless, and so I moved over to playing tennis. My mother had b
een quite a good tennis player. She liked it. And I found an old racquet of hers. And I suppose I also discovered, at that time, that girls played tennis and they didn\rquote t play cricket! (LAUGHS) That\rquote 
s another story. (LAUGHS) And then this caused more problems, because I turned out as quite a good tennis player, and I was playing for Yorkshire Juniors and so on. So there were always these problems with the school. In the first year, I wasn\rquote 
t in the top form, the A form, I was in the Alpha form, but after the f
irst year I was put in this S grade. We missed out the second year, you went straight from first year to S3. But I was never top at all. And then when I got into the sixth form, I was put in for \lquote A\rquote  Levels, after two years, and \lquote S
\rquote  Levels, which you had to take - but the idea was, this would just be practice year for \lquote S\rquote 
 Levels, you really did it all again in the third year. But I got a State Scholarship in the second year, and so this created a bit of a problem, because I think the school always regarded m
e as a bit of a maverick, and then the question was, should I be made a prefect when I got back (LAUGHS), or even Deputy Head Boy! And I think, growing up in this mining culture, I always regarded prefects as being \'93them\'94
, you know, on the other side. But 
I was to stay on at school for one more term, to try for Oxford and Cambridge. And I did, but it all ended in a bit of a mess, because I was seen at a jazz concert in Sheffield, with the French assistante, so it was suggested that perhaps it would be best
 if I left. (LAUGHS) I wanted to be a journalist at that point, so I got a job, really working for nothing, what would now be called an internship, of course \endash  though we didn\rquote t have them in those days \endash 
 on the local newspaper, South Yorkshire Times, because the Editor was a Yorkshire County tennis player, and so that helped. So from the Christmas through to going to university the next autumn, I worked on South Yorkshire Times. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
