\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh, absolutely. My two favourite subjects were histo
ry and maths, and, of course, in those days, they fell on the opposite side of the divide, but it was clear that I was going to go on the arts side because, at that stage, physics and chemistry did absolutely nothing for me. Biology, I had somewhat more i
nterest in. But it was clear I was always going to go on the arts side. But a rather strange thing happened, and it\rquote 
s fairly relevant to my later career, because I was in this S Form a year in advance, and the year I was due to take my first public examination, it was the first year when \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels took over from School Cert.. And in that year, for some reason, they put an age limit on, you had to be above a certain age, and I was just below it. My birthday was at the end of May, and these exams were earlier in the month, so I couldn\rquote 
t take them. The school was very sensible, they said, \'93Okay. You will have to take some exams internally, of the same standard, and if you do well enough in those, you can go on into the sixth form\'94. But there then is a problem, because you\rquote 
ve to make sure that you are matriculated \endash  in those days, the minimum requirement for going on to university. You had to have an \lquote  O\rquote  Level in English, which was okay, because I was going to take \lquote A\rquote  Level; an \lquote O
\rquote  Level in a modern languages, I was going to take French in the sixth form, so that was okay. But that left Latin and maths, and I needed to take \lquote O\rquote 
 Level in Latin and maths. So for that first year in the sixth form, I had, every week, just a one-on-one lesson with a teacher, to keep 
my Latin and maths up to speed. And the maths lessons, were with one of these rather sad people you found in grammar schools at that time - a lady, middle-aged lady, never married, of course, or she\rquote 
d have to stop teaching - who taught maths to the B and Beta forms, and taught the girls deportment and hygiene and things. She was wonderful! Really terrific maths teacher! So on one day - we used to have these lessons in the library \endash 
 just the one-on-one \endash  and I was waiting for her in the maths section of the library, and I saw, on the shelf, a book with this title, Mathematics for the Million. Yes, Lancelot Hogben. So I was looking through it, and she came in, and she said, 
\'93I suppose you\rquote ve discovered that it\rquote s not for the million, because it does get pretty tricky\'94, and I said, \'93Yeah, well, I\rquote ve just been looking at it\'94. And she said, \'93
Well, what we could do, we could work through parts of it\'94. Okay. And that was my introduction to statistics, and statistical thinking. I thought this was such a terrific book. So at the end of the year, I took the \lquote O\rquote 
 Level in maths and did quite well in it, but I can tell you now, or later, that had a very significant effect on my career, by a sheer fluke! Well, what happened was, after I took my degree in history \endash  I managed to get a First \endash 
 and so I got a Coal Miners Social Welfare Scholarship to do my graduate work, so the mining background came in well. And Tom Bottomore gave me some very good advice at that time. I met him at a conference for historians and sociologists, a
nd he told me there was a man at LSE, called John Smith, who was an industrial sociologist. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
