\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Exactly. That John Smith. And he would be the person to supervise me, because he did know this French tradi
tion. Bottomore had translated Georges Friedmann\rquote 
s book, [Industrial Society, 1955] which was, you know, like the text book for this. He knew that Smith knew this literature, so when I went to LSE to do a Ph.D. in Sociology, I was to be supervised by Smith
, who was in Social Policy, because this was where Nancy Sear\rquote s course on personnel management was, within Titmuss\rquote 
s Department. So, as a formality, just to keep the books straight, as it were, I had to have another formal supervisor in sociology. Glass wa
s professor and Head of Department, so he just took this on as a formality, but I was told that I should, as it were, pay a courtesy call on Glass. I knew nothing about Glass, and so I went to see him, and he just asked me about my background and so on, a
nd then what I was going to do and so on, and he said, \'93Do you have any mathematical background?\'94 And I said, \'93Well, no. I mean, I can only do \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels, but in this year in the sixth form, I did try and work through some of a book by Lancelot Hogben, Mathematics for the Million\'94. He looked at me, he said, \'93You\rquote ve read Hogben, Mathematics for the Million?\'94 He was Glass\rquote 
s supervisor! And Glass, apparently, had a pretty undistinguished first degree. Somebody told me \endash  I\rquote ve never checked on this \endash  he got a II 
ii in geography, but at the end of the thirties, Hogben had this Social Biology Unit at LSE, took Glass on, saw the talent, and Hogben was sort of classed as God. So, Glass, you know, said, \'93You ought to do what I\rquote m doing\'94
, and so on. So this sheer fluke! And he told me what he\rquote d been doing, this social mobility, and so I remember going off to the Economist Bookshop and buying Glass\rquote s book, and he told me about this other work in this field \endash 
 Svalastoga and G\'f6sta Carlsson in Sweden. This was kind of maths in sociology, and so this was a sheer fluke, just a chain of random events. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
