\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Well, no, that would be putting it too strongly. You see, the Glass project was twofold. One part, I discovered, one was to do with this first national study of soci
al mobility. The other, related to that, was to do a study of a whole series of new middle-class occupations, which Glass saw would be really driving social mobility in the second half of the 20th century, and that part was going to be more under the dire
ction of Tom Marshall, who was professor there, but then - for reasons I\rquote ve never understood \endash  although I got to know Marshall very well later, in Cambridge \endash 
 he decided to go off to UNESCO. So that part of the project was never fully realised. But you did 
have a group of graduate students who realised it in part. Asher Tropp did his book on school teachers, and looking at that as a source of development of primary school teaching, especially as a source of upward mobility for working-class kids, especially
 working-class women. Kelsall did his study of higher civil servants. Somebody else did a study of architects, and Lockwood, of course, did his Black Coated Worker.... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
