\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 It wasn\rquote t quite the same. They knew abou
t Everett Hughes work. But his concern was specifically with the occupation, and the kind of internal culture of the occupation. The LSE concern was more the role of these occupations in changing the class structure and creating opportunities for mobility
 - a different emphasis.... And, I mean, what was interesting for me, in Lockwood\rquote s work, was this kind of critique of Marxism and the idea that the big problem was, why don\rquote 
t these poorly-paid clerks, and lower level white-collar workers, join the working-class movement? - because, really, they\rquote re just objectively part of the proletariat? And the only reason they didn\rquote t, [the Marxists] explained with \'93
false consciousness\'94, which Lockwood just thought was no explanation at all. So he wanted to know why they had this so-called false consciousness, and that is what the book was about - and bringing in the idea of status to complement that of class 
\endash  which has always been a preoccupation of mine, and now, actually, in the work that I\rquote m doing at the moment, becomes quite central again. I talked a lot to Lockwood about this, and, of course, this was in the late fifties. I was at LSE
\rquote 56-\rquote 57. What was then becoming the issue, of course, was what was happening to the more affluent working class with Labour [election] failures. So we talked a bit about this. But we\rquote 
d no idea, at that point, of the Affluent Worker Study. Of course I then went off at the end of just one year at LSE, to teach at Leicester for three years, and it wasn\rquote t until we were back - I went to Cambridge in \rquote 
60, I think Lockwood came the next year, to a Lectureship - and then we resumed this. I mean, we\rquote d kept in touch over the period, but it was only after the 1959 Election, when Labour lost again, that this really became to the forefront, and we star
ted thinking about the Affluent Worker Project.... Sociology was expanding at that time, and I was amazed when, at the end of my first year, I got, well, two enquiries. One was from Bill Scott: would I like to go and work at Liverpool? They had this very 
active centre for research in industrial sociology, and he knew John Smith. And then, I think more through Glass, Neustadt heard about me, and he came down and - would I be interested in a job at Leicester? And I was a bit taken aback, because I\rquote 
d really on
ly been doing sociology one year! (LAUGHS) But, anyway the idea of an academic job, by then, had become attractive to me. I should say that it was during my second - really third year, in UCL, doing history, that I started being interested in an academic 
c
areer. And the professor there, Jimmy Neale, had me marked down to go to the Institute for Historical Research, to work on the history of Parliament, which did not appeal at all, and certainly not with Jimmy Neale! The other possibility was to work with N
amier, whom I\rquote d met, and if Namier had offered me something - but he didn\rquote t have anything - I might have gone, because I was a terrific admirer of Namier. But I\rquote 
d got more interested in these issues on the edge of history and sociology by then, so the idea of an academic job was great! So I decided to go to Leicester, because I was very impressed by Neustadt \endash 
 just as a character, strange. He was born in - well, geographically, Bessarabia, which was a disputed area, but at least he thought of himself as a Rumanian. He\rquote 
d originally thought about being a doctor, or a professional violinist. He was a superb violinist. But then decided he would do law, and with the Rumanian and French language connection, he went to Liege, and did a doctorate \endash  actually published 
\endash  on international law. He became somewhat interested in sociology, then in 1939, got one of the last boats out of Belgium, [came to England] and went to \'85
 to LSE and did a Ph.D. there, a sociological analysis of the industrialisation of Belgium \endash  a very interesting piece of work. And so he was a most engaging character. But the first year, \rquote 
57, he was going on sabbatical, to Ghana, to be Professor of Sociology at Accra for a year, so the only two permanent members of staff were Norbert Elias and myself, a
nd we did everything. We had some visiting lecturers, I think John Smith came up from LSE, somebody else came from Nottingham, and various other people. Leicester, at that time, was still a university college, it was just in transition to becoming a unive
rsity, so the second and third years were still doing the external London degree, and I got by teaching the paper on the Social Structure of Modern Britain. I\rquote d been to all Asher Tropp\rquote 
s lectures on that at LSE. (LAUGHS) But I had to read a lot. It wasn\rquote t helped by the fact that, at that time, I was playing a lot of tennis. I was, what, in those days, was called a \'93shamateur\'94 \'ac
- well, it was supposed to be amateur - but I wasn\rquote t good enough to be a shamateur in this country really, but I was in Ireland, so m
ost summers I took off and played round the tournament circuit in Ireland, and as a student, I made some money that way. (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
