\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, what happened was, you see, when I went there \endash  to Leicester \endash 
 after being a sociologist officially, for only a year, I really didn\rquote t know much about the subject. My views on it were very inchoate, and over the three years there, i
n that first year with Elias, and then after with Elias and Neustadt, we spent an enormous amount of time talking, if you like, about foundational issues, and I learnt an enormous amount from them. Because Neustadt, as I\rquote 
ve said, really came in this French tradition - he was steeped in Comte, he was a great admirer of Comte, always planned to write a great book on Comte \endash 
 unfortunately it never happened. Elias went to Heidelberg just after Max Weber died, but he was part of the Marianne Weber circle. He was
 a student with Mannheim, and so he was steeped in this German tradition. So one could learn a lot. But as we talked over these three years, I realised that there were some very big differences between us, and I never could accept Elias\rquote 
s, if you like, \'93system of sociology\'94. In fact, I wasn\rquote 
t sure that he had one. He was a brilliant, but I think idiosyncratic, one-off scholar. But the whole emphasis in Leicester was teaching sociology in a developmental and comparative way, and with the comparative part I was entirely happy. I\rquote 
ve done a lot of comparative work myself. I was never quite sure what they meant about \'93development\'94, whether they regarded this as being purely a descriptive concept so that you could look back at the past and say, \'93This is how it developed\'94
, or whether it did have some more historicist, teleological element \endash  they knew where it was going. I never thought that Elias came out absolutely clearly one way or the other on this. I think he really did feel that there was some kind of inheren
t
 dynamic in the movement of human societies, and we also used to have big arguments about his developmental approach, especially this idea, I remember that he had this notion of increasing individuation, and wanted to allege that individuation was less in
 stateless societies. And I\rquote d always been a great reader since I found them at primary school of Icelandic/Nordic sagas, and these were about stateless societies. But anybody who\rquote 
s read those could not believe that the characters in them were not individuat
ed, even allowing for the fact that it seems most of the sagas were written a couple of centuries later than the times they referred to. So I never bought into this link between greater individuation and state formation. And a lot of other things. So that
 was one. And then the other was - I thought - their pretty na\'efve approach towards quantification. They never really, seemed to me, to grasp the role of it. It wasn\rquote t that they didn\rquote t understand the statistics \endash 
 neither had any statistical training at all - but that wasn\rquote t the main problem. I don\rquote 
t think they ever saw how a lot of the things one wants to study in sociology, and say in sociology, have to be expressed, to some extent, quantitatively. Having discovered the Glass approach at LSE, really there we
re two people, in a way, at LSE, that stood between me and the Elias-Neustadt tradition. One was Popper, because at LSE I went to Popper\rquote s lectures, and I thought they were superb \endash 
 wonderful clarity and simplicity of thought, but very deep ideas, and I always thought that, in some ways, Elias was a covert historicist in the Popperian sense. And then Glass. And also I should say, inspired by Glass, I went to Claus Moser\rquote 
s lectures on quantitative methods for sociologists, and they were superb. Claus was wonderful, because he didn\rquote 
t make any big mathematical demands. He really taught statistics more from the point of view of the logic of what it was about, and he told me, some years after, that he was terrified when Allen, who was Professor of Statistics ther
e, told him that he would have to give these lectures. Because Claus, in a way, never thought that he knew much about theoretical mathematical aspects of statistics. He was very much an applied man in descriptive statistical data analysis. But it was an i
nspired choice by Allen because Claus did it in his own way without making any big demands on mathematics. He said, \'93Look, if you want to know the underlying theory of what I\rquote 
m saying, then you can go here and here and read the maths, but from the point of people who are not statisticians, but want to use statistics, and want to have a decent competence in data analysis, this is what you need to know\'94
. And they were magnificent lectures. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Remind me, just quickly, which Allen was that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
