\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Okay. That\rquote s not a problem. Two or three times you\rquote ve said something very very interesting, which was, \'93
I read a book, but my observation, myself, said it wasn\rquote t like that\'94. Jackson and Marsden, and Dennis, Henriques and Slaughter, and now you\rquote re saying, with respect to Norbert and Elias that somehow or other they\rquote 
re ignoring the empirical material. Is that a fair statement of what you regard as important? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, I wouldn\rquote t say they were disregarding empirical material. Another problem with Norbert - although he probably wouldn
\rquote t agree to this \endash  I did find his whole approach too inductive. He had the idea - he\rquote s written this down in several places - that you have an idea \endash 
 you pay and he paid enormous attention to empirical material, historical material, and then, if that doesn\rquote t quite fit the idea, you adjust it. It was an early version of what\rquote s become known as \'93grounded theory\'94
, where you constantly adapt your theoretical, or at any rate, your conceptual position, to new data. And as somebody influenced by Popper, I felt that was a bit of a cop-out. I mean, at some point I think
 you have to come forward with a clear testable proposition, and see whether it stands up against the empirical data. And, okay, you may want to refine it a bit, and modify it, but you\rquote 
ve always to keep in mind that, at some point, you may have to say, \'93No. That\rquote s wrong!\'94 (LAUGHS) And start again \endash 
 not this endless adjustment and adaptation. And so that was a worry. And also, that said, I felt that some of the issues they wanted to raise were inherently quantitative \endash  and this was more a problem with Elias than Neustadt, because in Neustadt
\rquote s doctoral thesis on industrialisation of Belgium, he did have a lot of descriptive statistical material, and used it very well. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 

