\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
No, no, but I just would like to make that clear that there was never - well, Neustadt had a very sad ending: in that when he retired, I\rquote d already come to Nuffield, and I\rquote d arranged for him to come to Nuffield for a year, sabbatical year 
\endash  either before or after he retired \endash  partly to write this book on Comte. He\rquote 
d another book always on the stocks, on the division of labour, perhaps a Reader with a lot of different pieces going back to the 17th century on the division of labour. And then he got Parkinson\rquote 
s, and he became very, very sensitive about it, and he wouldn\rquote t come. And I went to see him a couple of times but he somehow didn\rquote t seem to welcome visits. We talked a lot on the telephone, and he became more and more reclusive. He
 just had one or two students who I think looked after him very well until the end, and junior lecturers at Leicester. Elias was most unsympathetic about this. And really, Neustadt had rescued Elias, when he was an \'e9migr\'e9
, and given him this job at Leicester \endash  got him a Readership, got him a Chair \endash  and I don\rquote 
t know, really, what happened, but it was very sad. And, of course, this was just at the point when Elias was being rediscovered and becoming a great figure, while his Leicester years were really years
 of relative obscurity. But anyway, on the question of quantitative versus qualitative, I think my position on that really only began to change during the time in Cambridge. I mean, the Affluent Worker project wasn\rquote 
t especially quantitative. It was designe
d as a critical case study, and okay, we took samples and we had some tables, but, I mean, apart from the odd significance test, there was no multivariate analysis in it at all. I did, though, start then - this was the first time I got sort of academicall
y
 interested in social mobility as such. With Glass it was more a way of seeing how, as it were, quantitative thinking could fit into sociology, and it just happened that the subject was social mobility. But then in Cambridge, sociology, at that time, was 
taught in the Economics Faculty, and one of the three compulsory papers in Part II of the Economics Tripos was a paper called \'93Economic and Social Relations\'94. It was taught jointly by sociologists and economists, and there were three parts \endash 
 one on individu
al and family as consumer and spender; one on the economic and social organisation of the enterprise; and the other on labour mobility and social mobility. Initially I taught the course on the enterprise, with Robin Marris, who was a colleague of mine at 
King\rquote s, but then I moved over to teaching the labour mobility and social mobility part of the course, and that\rquote 
s when I really, for the first time, started reading the more recent work on social mobility, and became interested in it. Then I became aware tha
t I did need to improve my statistical knowledge, because by that time you had people like Otis Dudley Duncan in the States using regression approaches to social mobility, and then developing these into causal path analysis. So I began to be more aware, t
here, of how relatively advanced statistical techniques could have major sociological potential. I guess what further changed my view was, by the end of the sixties, one had \endash  well, in Britain and elsewhere \endash  this so-called \'93
reaction against positivism\'94, and then the attacks on quantitative methods, and I thought \endash  and I still think \endash  that was the big disaster in British sociology, and I really didn\rquote 
t have much sympathy, or very much patience, to be honest, with the various alternatives that were floated around, ranging from phenomenology and ethnomethodology at one extreme to weird forms of structuralist Marxism, Althusser, et.al \endash 
 at the other. I thought that was going nowhere. Well, at that time I was asked about coming to Oxford, because Chelly Halsey and
 Jean Floud here were planning this mobility study, and they asked me if I would be interested in coming to Nuffield as an Official Fellow and joining in this, because I\rquote 
d produced one or two working papers on social mobility and I actually gave a talk her
e on, based on one of them, based on the lecture notes that I had at Cambridge. So this opportunity came up. And at the same time, in Cambridge, they were developing this new Social and Political Sciences Tripos, and I didn\rquote 
t much like the way that was going. The anthropologists were having too much influence, and rather than appointing Lockwood as Professor, they appointed an anthropologist as Professor of Sociology \endash 
 John Barnes. Yes, nice man, but it seemed to me that wasn\rquote t the way the subject should be going. So I decided to leave [Cambridge]. It wasn\rquote 
t too difficult a decision for me, but there were problems because my wife was teaching, she was a Lecturer in French at Cambridge, and a Fellow at Newnham. So it was a big decision in that way. And our fi
rst child had been born. But in the end we decided to move to Oxford. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
