\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
He was. And he, of course, made this bridge between sociologie du travail and sociology. His first [work] - I think his thesis with Friedmann was on the evolution of work at the Renault factories, and that 
was a very important book. But then, because of what I think of as the unfortunate aspects of French intellectual culture, to get his big thesis, he had to write some large theoretical work which I don\rquote 
t think went anywhere at all. It was a great pity. And I\rquote 
d somewhat closer contacts with Michel Crozier, and with a man called Jean-Daniel Reynaud at the Ecole de Mines, and with some of the younger persons like a friend of mine, Alfred Willener. So I suppose I had some French background but I suppose, also, we
\rquote 
d somewhat similar background. I mean, we were both, as it were, non-Cambridge people in Cambridge. My wife was educated at Bangor, and then she had a teaching job at Glasgow, and she came from a somewhat similar background to mine, but one generation r
emoved. Her grandparents were miners and metalworkers in South Wales, but her father had taken a degree in English. He had been very much on the Left \endash  member of the ILP \endash 
and was jailed in the First World War for refusing to fight. And so yes, it\rquote s quite interesting. It was the same, but as I say, one generation further back. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
