\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 No. That\rquote s quite an interesting story as well! Chance comes in again. I deferred \endash 
 well, go back a step. When I was at school, in the sixth form, and first had to register, I expressed a preference for the Royal Air Force, and then after I got my first degree, I decided to apply for deferment - I thought I\rquote 
d like to get my Ph.D. first. And during that time I heard from various contacts that a really attractive way of doing National Service was to go 
into the Navy and learn Russian. There was a course for people who had got good degrees, to learn Russian, and then you went into Naval Intelligence \endash 
 there was a Russian course in Cambridge. So I applied to change my preference to the Navy. Well, then aft
er one year as a graduate student, as I said, I got this job at Leicester, and I explained this to them there that I was still on deferment, so technically, my post there wasn\rquote 
t called an Assistant Lecturer, it was called Junior Research Fellow, although I
 was doing the job of Assistant Lecturer and paid as Assistant Lecturer. Then I heard that I was in line to go into Naval Intelligence, and so I was thinking, after three years at Leicester, that would be it, I\rquote 
d have to go off into the Navy. And then something very strange happened. The UGC \endash  University Grants Committee \endash 
 in those days, yeah, visited Leicester. They used to come around, apparently, and discuss with Vice-Chancellors and leading figures in Senate, what the future development of universities 
should be. And Leicester had just got its Charter, and apparently UGC said they really liked the Sociology Department at Leicester, and really felt it should expand, and they would have money for expansion. And the Vice-Chancellor, whose name I forget at 
the moment, he was a very feisty Glaswegian political theorist, and he said, \'93Well, this was fine\'94
 - but the problem was getting good quality people to teach. Because, of course, the subject had not existed, and it was absurd that one of his best young teac
hers, in a year or so, would have to leave to do National Service. He must have been pretty forceful on this, because he then summoned me - I went to see him and he said he\rquote 
d made this point, and he had a letter from the UGC, backed up by whatever it was called \endash  the recruiting people \endash 
 to say that for so long as I taught sociology at Leicester, I would be exempt from National Service! Which was very nice! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 What happened at the end of the three years? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Ah well, wait! It gets even more
 complicated! Then a year later, I got this Prize Fellowship at Cambridge, and so, before I signed on the dotted line, as it were, I went to see the Provost \endash  Noel Annan \endash  and said, \'93
Look, there is this slight difficulty, that my exemption from National Service is only for so long as I\rquote m teaching sociology at Leicester. There could be a problem\'94
. But at that time, this was 1960, National Service was really winding down, it was clear they didn\rquote t want to go on with it, and Annan, somewhat to my surprise said, \'93Oh, leave it with me\'94
. And he called me back while I was still in Cambridge, I think, after I\rquote d been elected, and said, \'93It\rquote s all right.\'94 I wondered, you know, how could this man do this? And he\rquote 
d asked me, you know, where I was scheduled to go, and I said, \'93Well, I was hoping it would be Naval Intelligence\'94. I later discovered he\rquote d been a big shot in Intelligence in the War, so he\rquote 
d obviously called somebody. (LAUGHS) But I think, by that time, you know, a lot of people were being told they didn\rquote t have t
o go, it was all running down. So by these flukes, I managed to avoid National Service. Then what was strange was that when in Cambridge, this lady who taught the Russian course, turned out to be a colleague of my wife\rquote s in Newnham \endash 
 she was the Russian do
n there. She was apparently a brilliant Russian teacher, but really quite crazy. She was an absolutely fervent believer in astrology. And the first thing she did, anyone who came on her course, she plotted their star chart, or whatever you call it, and th
e
re was a feeling that how well you did really depended on what she thought the stars foretold for you. Also I discovered that it was a very intense course. You were examined every two or three weeks. If you failed, you were out. I mean, out of the course,
 
you were on the deck and scrubbing it. And then even if you passed, [where] you most likely ended up was on a destroyer somewhere up in the Barents Sea, shadowing the Russian fleet, and probably being violent seasick the while. So the accounts I heard lat
er didn\rquote t really tally with the accounts I heard earlier, so I was quite pleased to have missed this course! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
