\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Oh, good Heavens, yes! I was the last generation to have to get an Intermediate Degree in Latin, [in the] first year if they were doing arts at UCL. This was really agonising, because you had to pass or you were thrown out \endash 
 no matter how well you were doing at history, or whatever other subject. Yet you didn\rquote t want to spend more time on this than you had to. I thought I would do something very smart, and I got the University Calendar, and looked up \endash 
 during my year as a journalist this was - what the set book was for this course, and okay, it\rquote s Catullus\rquote s poetry, so I got this, and I thought, \'93I will get ahead of the game\'94
, so that few months I read Catullus and so on. Of course, when I got there, I found out I\rquote d made a mistake. I\rquote 
d looked at the wrong year, and it was Book 4 [of the Aeneid]. So yes, it was a problem. I came out of it with all sorts of dishonour because I was really scared of failing - the ideal was to get a Third and among my colleagues, I was thought to h
ave disgraced myself because I got a II: ii! (LAUGHS) ... Well, after my year, they stopped. But it was helpful, actually, in one way, because later on I did a course in Mediaeval Latin, which really was useful for the history - which was much easier, of 
course, than classical Latin, but still the classical Latin helped... Well, I just saw, reviewed in the papers, this weekend, somebody\rquote s produced a book, How to Read a Latin Poem, and I thought, \'93I wonder if I might go back to Catullus\'94
, but I\rquote ve probably too many other things to do! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
