\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Okay. So we\rquote ve got you to studying history and that\rquote 
s when your interest in social economic history was really crystallising? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes... It was. You see, in this time, there were great debates among Marxist scholars about whether we\rquote 
d really ever had a feudal system in this country \endash  England, that is \endash  whether we\rquote d ever really had a peasantry. And it\rquote s curious, you had a lot of White Russians who\rquote 
d come over here, like Postan, who I later got to know well in Cambridge, but then, at that time, there were some very distinguished Soviet historians doing very nitty-gritty work on agrarian history \endash 
 Kosminsky, Semeonov. So we had to know all this stuff, so that got me into a lot of Marxist theory. And then, of cour
se, on the whole question of the development of capitalism, we came across Weber. I came across him in a very odd way. We had one lecturer I did not like. There was a man called Joel Hurstfield, and he represented Weber as some kind of mad German. And one
 of my closest friends, an undergraduate \endash  a man called Alan Millward, who became a very distinguished economic historian later \endash  and I remember saying, \'93This is an interesting idea this, that there\rquote 
s a link between Protestantism and Capitalism\'94, you know, \'93Who was this mad German?\'94 So I remember, we went to the library together, and then we realised, no, this man wasn\rquote t mad at all, this man was really smart, and we\rquote 
d been given just a ridiculous caricature of his arguments by Hurstfield \endash  whom we both loath
ed! So we started reading Weber. So I had got a pretty good background in Marx and Weber, and this was obviously another influence moving me towards sociology. Because a lot of this French sociologie du travail, had a Marxist or marxisant inspiration, so 
it really did all fit together. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So would you say that the founding fathers, as it were, that you moved towards, were Marx and Weber? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
