\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 No. Not until I was at LSE, and then I read Durkheim, and I\rquote ve never been a Durkheim admirer. I\rquote 
ve always felt that he did more damage to sociology (LAUGHS) than good! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Is it possible to characterise what was that damage that he did? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I think he - to put it very crudely - had a basic holistic conception of society, exaggerated \endash  in my view \endash 
 to an impossible degree, and over-emphasised, seriously, the extent to which individuals, their actions and relationships, were not just conditione
d, but really very clearly moulded by socio-cultural factors. And too much mysticism about these courants suicidog\'e8nes that somewhere exist up here [POINTS UPWARDS]. I found it too mystical. And then, although he\rquote 
s always presented as the great pioneer of quantitative sociological analysis in Suicide, I think that\rquote 
s really a myth, because his whole basic method is logical analysis, and Durkheim really had no idea of correlation. If you look at his arguments in Suicide, they all suppose that something is correlated, or associated, with something else \endash 
 either totally or not at all. The correlation coefficient is either 1 or 0, and there\rquote s nothing in between. And so it was, in many ways, a profoundly non-statistical way of using quantitative evidence. And, you
 know, it has been shown to be defective. I also felt he was far too rhetorical. Some of his arguments are much more based on rhetoric than really hard logic in every sense.... So although there\rquote 
s some aspects of French social thought that obviously attracted me from the start, Durkheim didn\rquote t figure. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 What about Comte? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 

\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Well, a fascinating development in history of social thought. When I was in Cambridge, the other course I had to lecture on was History of Social Thought, so I started off wit
h Montesquieu, and the Scots Moralists, and then through Comte. So I read a lot of Comte \endash  with Neustadt\rquote s guidance \endash  and, no, again, I think, for me, he has a basically wrong concept [of society]. Looking back now, I couldn\rquote 
t say, really, when these ideas
 first developed. For me, the really important sort of historical figure, on the theoretical side, [was] Weber. But then, what I think is very neglected in the way sociology is taught, [are] the early pioneers of more quantitative social research. I think
 a very neglected figure is Quetelet, and I\rquote ve written quite a bit about Quetelet. And then, also the British empiricist tradition, going back to the political arithmeticians of the 17th century. That\rquote s the kind of sociological tradition 
\endash  as far as empirical research is concerned \endash  that I find most inspiring. And then more on the theoretical side, more the German tradition - well, Weber just really does dominate in that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Is it really class and status in that respect? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
