\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
No, because it has some other philosophical meanings. It can be a bit confusing. But I really do think that in social life, causal efficacy \endash  if you want to put it that way \endash 
 ultimately resides in individual action. Of course, this action is always conditioned by social phenomena which have their own sui generis existence. I think it\rquote 
s very important to make a distinction between methodological individualism and ontological individualism. I mean, I don\rquote t agree with Mrs. Thatcher when she said, \'93There is no such thing as society\'94
. Obviously social phenomena have their own reality, but if you want to explain them, then in the end it has to come down to individual action. That\rquote s the methodological individualism. I\rquote m not satisfied with sociological e
xplanations, for example, that end with social norms, or institutions embodying social norms, because the question always is, \'93
Well, why these social norms, rather than some other social norms? Why do people follow these social norms rather than break them?\'94 So explanations that just end with social norms, I find really unsatisfactory. I\rquote 
ve more sympathy, in a way, with explanations that emphasise non-normative constraints - I mean, \'93purely factual\'94 as Lockwood would say, or \'93material constraints\'94, because 
they obviously do limit the choices of action that individuals can make. But even then, the feasible set of actions for people in some of the worst material conditions, the most constrained, the choices they have are still not nothing. There\rquote 
s always some choice, \'85 they may have nothing but bad choices, but at least they choose among bad choices! (LAUGHS) And again, then you need to know, \'93
Well, how do these structural constraints that bear so heavily, perhaps, on certain sections of a population, come to be as they are?\'94 Again, I think the explanation has to be, ultimately, in terms of individual action and interaction. I\rquote 
m just writing something at the moment \endash  I don\rquote t know whether it\rquote ll ever be finished \endash  on sociology as a population science. And the basi
c idea is that what we can best be concerned with, in sociology, is thinking about populations and sub-populations, rather than socio-cultural entities, and trying to establish - and here, I think, statistical methods are foundational - various empirical 
regularities in these populations, of many different kinds, most of which are rather opaque regularities \endash  we don\rquote t know what\rquote s generating them \endash 
 and then to come up with theories about the actual social mechanisms that generate these regularities; and these mechanisms to be given in terms of, as it were, generalised narratives of action and interaction, and that\rquote s really \endash 
 when I look back on it \endash  what I\rquote ve mainly been doing, or trying to do, for the last 20 or 30 years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Are you writing a book, or are you just doing a series of papers? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
