\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Well, I think the 
Affluent Worker studies were only pioneering in one sense, and that is that they were really the first studies to be done in Britain, with public money \endash  in part public money from what was then the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research 
\endash  that weren\rquote 
t directly oriented to some applied issue. DSIR was supposed only to fund research that could, in some way, contribute to productivity, but when we were planning the Affluent Worker studies, the head of that Section of DSIR was this marvellous man, Alb
ert Cherns, who was very responsive to what we wanted to do, and very indulgent. We had to put in a proposal that suggested it had some potential contribution to productivity, but we knew, and he knew, that this was all a bit of a front. We got the money,
 
and obviously the research itself was prompted by a political issue, not by concerns for raising industrial productivity. So I think it was original in that sense. We were trying to take a sociological issue that had achieved some prominence because of po
litical circumstances \endash 
 the failure of the Labour Party, yet again, at the 1959 Election, and all the debate about whether they should change course because the working-class was changing in its nature. So we were able to devise a specifically sociological 
piece of research and get at least some funding from a State agency. Although, at the same time, it should be said that the Department of Applied Economics at Cambridge put more money into the project than DSIR.... What they did, I mean, they made posts a
vailable to us. You see, they allowed us to advertise for a couple of research posts which were paid for on their budget. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So was that Frank Bechhofer and Jennifer Platt? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 It was. So otherwise, I don\rquote t think there\rquote s anything remarkably new in 
the Affluent Worker studies. We developed a new approach in industrial sociology. I very much changed tack from my earlier interest in what you might call \'93technological implications\'94
. We did pick the three firms with that approach in mind, and especially 
under the influence of this work by an American sociologist, Robert Blauner, but we realised, as the results came in, that effects of technology were really very limited, and we developed this idea of \'93orientations to work\'94
. Again, it fitted in with my general view that what\rquote s important are individuals\rquote 
 actions, the goals that they have, and interactions with others that this leads them into. I always remember, coming from a mining background, what really struck me, they had this phrase - we asked them, in 
the interviews, how often men we interviewed saw people they worked with outside of work. Scarcely ever. And the phrase that came out, \'93mates aren\rquote t friends\'94
. Now, in a mining context, a mining community, that would have made no sense at all. Your mates we
re your friends... But, of course, then you think about it, and yes, it makes sense, because the people you were working with, you had a very close relationship with them, because your safety as well as your earnings, depended absolutely on them.... I was
 a bit surprised, to be honest, about the way The Affluent Worker became sort of enshrined in British sociology. I mean, only a few years ago, Cambridge reprinted it, and in some ways, to be honest, I think it\rquote s a pity, I don\rquote 
t think undergraduates in British sociology departments should be reading The Affluent Worker now. I think it should have been consigned to history 20/30 years ago. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 What should they be reading now? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, much rather they read my work on social mobility! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
