\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Yes. Much better candidate, not in the sense that we did a national survey, because Glass did the first national survey, but I think we were able, for the first time,
 in a national survey, to really get to grips with some fundamental, conceptual issues in studying mobility, and to translate these into appropriate statistical techniques. What we planned to do originally \endash 
 and this was really Chelly Halsey and Jean Floud\rquote s idea \endash 
 was to do a study that would, on the one hand, replicate Glass, and so bring Glass up to date, and allow for comparisons over time with Glass, and secondly, would replicate Blau and Duncan with their more advanced regression methods, and allow a 
comparison between Britain and the United States. And what we discovered, in the early years of the project - and I think I was quite heavily involved in this \endash  that neither of these two things was, in fact, possible. We couldn\rquote 
t replicate Glass because th
e basic coding in Glass, of occupations, was to the Hall-Jones Scale, which was defective in many ways, and there was no clear guidance, no clear manual for doing this coding. The two documents that were available were contradictory in regard to many occu
pations. And we couldn\rquote t get the original schedules to re-code the data. John Ridge and Kenneth MacDonald spent many weeks trying to track these down. We thought we\rquote 
d traced them to a warehouse in Neasden, of all places! We got a shelf reference to this warehouse, and when they got there, the shelf was empty. Probably they\rquote d been destroyed. It is possible that they\rquote d just got misplaced. I don\rquote 
t know whether this warehouse in Neasden still exists, but I suppose it\rquote s possible they might still surface. So all t
hat was left from the Glass study were the punched cards, but the coding was already in there. Then with the Blau and Duncan approach, this involved in having continuous scales of occupations. They used the Duncan SEI Index - and also of education 
\endash  they used years of education. Well, years of education didn\rquote 
t make all that much sense in Britain, with the kind of educational system that we had. But more to the point, the majority of people in the sample that we took in 1972 had minimal education. They left 
school at the end of compulsory education. So to try and standardise a distribution of that kind, where you got this great block with the same value, made no sense. I also became more and more doubtful about the methodology of causal path analysis, and th
a
t, in a way, came from my background with Glass, because there are really two traditions, certainly in British statistics: one really that wants to translate everything into continuous variables, going back to Karl Pearson, and the other that Yule pioneer
e
d, of giving a very clear place for analysis of categorical data, and Glass was very much in that tradition. So Glass was very sceptical about path analysis on statistical grounds, and so was I. Mainly because the results you would get are based on the as
sumption that the same regression rules apply across the whole population, and nobody believes that\rquote 
s true. There are different degrees of association between social origins and eventual destinations, depending on what your social origins were. You can aim to capture it all in one number, but I think that\rquote 
s very misleading.... Let me just give one very clear example of that. Take people who grow up in families of small entrepreneurs - small shopkeepers, small builders, craftsmen. We know that the sons have a
 very high propensity to follow on. They inherit the business, and take it over. So there\rquote s a much stronger propensity for immobility, given those origins, than if your father, say, was a clerk, or a wage worker. It\rquote s not uniform, you can
\rquote t capture it in o
ne single set of regression rules. So we moved towards this categorical approach, and I developed this class schema. This meant we needed an appropriate method of statistical analysis that would handle categorical data. Glass had used categorical data, bu
t then the big problem with his work was that he never \endash  well, it really wasn\rquote t available in those days \endash 
 [had the] appropriate statistical technique to handle data of this kind, and so his way of trying to measure the association between - well, it was Hal
l-Jones category of father and of child - was inadequate. This index of mobility had serious statistical flaws. So we struggled with this for a while, and then it was actually at an ISA meeting in Poland, a place near Warsaw, that I saw the way ahead. I
\rquote d been working with disparity ratios, not a very good statistical measure, and then Bob Hauser gave a paper there on \'93log-linear modelling\'94 \endash  which I knew nothing about \endash 
 and began by saying the basic element of all log-linear models is an odds ratio, and I realised, as he put the algebra on the board, that an odds ratio was simply the product of two complementary disparity ratios that I\rquote 
d been working with. And then as he went on, it became clear to me that this was the technique that we needed. Because this could solve the old problem of how you dealt with what used to be called \'93structural\'94 and \'93exchange mobility\'94
. That was never a satisfactory way of looking at it, and partitioning mobility into structural and exchange had all kinds of problems. Bob was a student of Dudley Duncan\rquote s, and he had also got together with a very good American statistician 
\endash  Leo Goodman, who really developed log linear modelling and analysis of contingency tables generally \endash  and I don\rquote t think Bob fully saw the possibilities for us
ing log linear modelling in a mobility context, even though he was working in that field, because he was still very much oriented towards the Duncan style of path analysis. But for me, it was just the tool that I wanted, and I came back to Oxford and said
, \'93Who can teach me log-linear modelling? This is what we need\'94. And we had a whole battery of high powered quantitative people here \endash 
 Kenneth MacDonald, John Ridge, a man called Paul Duncan-Jones, Keith Hope, himself, who had been working with me on this \endash  they didn\rquote t know what I was talking about. The one person who said, \'93
I know about log linear modelling, I can teach you\'94, was Clive Payne, who was here, running the Computing Unit. I think, often, by these high-tech whiz kids, he was a bit looked down on 
as a kind of technician. He taught me log linear modelling. We did some papers together. And that, I think alongside Hauser\rquote s work, really did revolutionise the field, and this led, then, to the distinction that I made \endash 
 I think I did pioneer this \endash  betwee
n absolute and relative mobility rates, which, I think, is quite fundamental to understanding social mobility. And I think what is important about this is that it shows how conceptual development and development in quantitative analysis really have to go 
together. This is why I get a bit annoyed when people just talk about number crunching, because they don\rquote 
t see that analysing the numbers, and grappling with the quantitative problems, can give you new conceptual insights about how you should think about the sociological problem that you\rquote 
ve got. So that was really, I think, the main achievement of British mobility work. Then I moved on, some years after that, to start doing more comparative work with Robert Erikson, and Lucienne Portocarero in Stockholm. The
 first issue we took up then was how to get truly comparable cross-national data, and I don\rquote t think anybody had taken that seriously before. So we developed a version of the class schema that I\rquote 
d used in the Oxford mobility study. It turned out that Erikson had developed a very similar schema for the Swedish Statistical Office, so we put these together \endash  they were very close anyway \endash  in what became known as the \'93EGP class schema
\'94. Then we took a whole lot of data sets from different countries and spent two or three years re-coding all this data to this EGP class schema. And also a common educational classification. I don\rquote 
t think anybody had done that before and we regarded it as taking data seriously, because what people had done before - like Lipset, and a lot of people following Lipset - when they\rquote d compared mobility data between different countries, they\rquote 
d simply taken the categories that the original investigators used, and tried to collapse them down to some common denominator, which usually ended up just being \'93manual\'94, \'93non-manual\'94, and even then it wasn\rquote 
t always very precisely done. So that was one contribution really - to take data seriously. And what was fascinating was that as we worked on this and tried to get the data more uniform, we did find tha
t the extent of cross-national differences, in many respects \endash  especially as regards relative rates \endash  diminished. So before, I think a lot of people had been finding differences that were largely artifactual because they hadn\rquote 
t made sure that they\rquote d got good comparative data. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Can I ask two quick questions about this period of work. Does the development of computing help? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
