\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh, enormously.... You see, the principles of log-linear modelling, in a way, were discovered in Cambridge in the 1930s by
 a man called Bartlett, and he did write something on analysis of 2 x 2 x 2 tables, and the problems that stood in the way of taking it further were computational. And Goodman, when he started working on this in the sixties, did produce the first programm
e for doing log-linear modelling. It was called \'93ECTA\'94 \endash  Everyman\rquote s Contingency Table Analysis. But it did it in a very long-winded way \endash 
 judging it from the standpoint of the present. I mean, it was a great achievement when he did it. And when Clive Payne 
and I started working with ECTA here, fitting very, very simple log linear models, we got a message from the Oxford Computing Service - you see, what happened was, we would send our models to the Oxford Computer, it couldn\rquote 
t handle them. So it sent them then to London, and often London couldn\rquote 
t handle them. So the biggest computer was Manchester, and it went to Manchester, and it took us two or three days to get a result back. And, of course, it cost the University every time they passed it on, and Manchest
er charged a lot. So we got this message from the Head of Computing Services saying did we realise that our computing costs were second highest in the University, exceeded only by those of Dorothy Hodgkin in the crystallography laboratory, who had just wo
n the Nobel Prize! (LAUGHS) So no, we didn\rquote t realise that, but what could we do? Fortunately, just about at that point, computer speeds were increasing very rapidly, and then somebody came up with a different way of fitting these models \endash 
 a Group actually in Oxford \endash  and they produced a programme called GLIM, that did the whole thing in a much more efficient way, and so we were saved! But this couldn\rquote t have been done without a quite high degree of computing power. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
