\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh, that was a big story! We applied to what was then SSRC, and this would be in the early seventies \endash 
 and we had a site visit from people from SSRC. We explained that we wanted to run the survey ourselves. We would put it out to a fieldwork agency, but we
 would really want to tell the agency what they had to do. We would devise the interview schedule, we would be in charge of all the piloting of it with the interviewers, and we would monitor the results. And we discussed, with them, how much money it woul
d be feasible to apply for. I think our limit was about \'a3
80,000, and we discussed, with them, what size of sample we should have. A point that became very debated later - and made me very angry - we discussed explicitly with them: whether we should limit to
 men, or include how many women, pointing out that if we took in women, then given the budgetary constraints they imposed upon us, we wouldn\rquote 
t be able to do the same degree of cross birth-cohort analysis. It had to go one way or the other. We did apply, an
d we discovered this only afterwards: we were turned down by the Sociology Committee, but we were supported by the Statistics Committee. Andrew Shonfield then had a difficult decision to make \endash  he was Chief Executive or Chairman or whatever 
\endash  and he decide
d, and he told us afterwards, perhaps ultra vires, that the grant would go through. That was my first experience of how real, in British sociology, the reaction against positivism was, and the hostility to quantitative research. Because such information a
s we were given as to why the Sociology Committee turned it down, seemed to amount to little more than that \endash  that they didn\rquote 
t like quantitative research, and they felt too much money was going to quantitative research. Another thing that irritated me greatly was that when all the to do started afterwards, about why we\rquote 
d not included women, one of the Feminist cheerleaders on this was Margaret Stacey, who\rquote d been a member of the site visiting party here, and had never raised that issue or said anything about it when she came here. So I wasn\rquote 
t too impressed by her performance, in that respect. But anyway, we got the money, and we found a very good fieldwork agency \endash  no longer exists - called the Mary Agar Agency, a one woman organisation, and Mary Agar was terr
ific, and we worked very well with her, and the actual data collection operation went remarkably well. The only problem we had was in College, because all through one Long Vacation we wanted to use two rooms that were lecture rooms at that time, in Colleg
e
, for the coding. We wanted to supervise the coding very closely, and all the coders were down there, and they had 10,000 interview schedules to code, and some of the older Fellows of the College thought this was turning the place into a research institut
e and not how an Oxford College should be and so on. So we had quite a battle over that! But going back, then, to the comparative work, we did a little pilot study just of England, Sweden and France \endash 
 Erikson, and Portocarero and I - then we launched this b
ig CASMIN Project, and by that time I realised I would get no support for my kind of research in this country. So we went to Volkswagen Foundation, and we got a very good grant from Volkswagen, provided the project was based in Germany, in Mannheim, and a
ll the money was spent on German research staff, as it were \endash 
 which was fair enough. But they were very good funders: minimal interference. So we started off on this Casmin Project, and the first two/two and a half years were really this massive re-coding e
xercise. Then we started doing analyses, and one big sociological issue was whether relative rates of social mobility had become more equal or, in other words, whether social fluidity had increased, net of any changes coming about from the changing shapes
 of the class structures, which were big in themselves. But if you wanted to get to the inherent, if you like, \'93stickiness\'94 in the relationship between parents\rquote 
 class position and their children, net of all these structural changes, we knew how to do that from log-linear modelling. But then the question was: ... we know how to test the hypothesis that there was no difference across these countries \endash 
 what we call the \'93constant social fluidity hypothesis\'94 - but what if there was some gradual change towards eit
her greater social fluidity or less? How could we capture that? And this was a big problem. And I worked a bit on it with Clive Payne, and a statistician from Liverpool, and we got nowhere. And then Robert Erikson and I, talking to a demographer in Stockh
olm, Jan Hoem, we came up with a log multiplicative model, and it was a bit of home-made statistics, in a way, and we weren\rquote 
t sure. But fortunately, just at that time, David Cox had become Warden here, and even then, and certainly now, I would regard him as the greatest statistician in the world, and a remarkable man. So I didn\rquote t know him very well then, he\rquote 
d only been Warden for a few months, so we said could we show him this model? And we went along with a little worked example, and he looked at it, and he said, \'93Yes. I like that. You can do that\'94. He said, \'93The pure mathematicians won\rquote 
t like it, because you\rquote re multiplying logs, and mathematicians don\rquote t like multiplying logs, it\rquote s inelegant\'94. But he says, \'93Never mind. I think it works\'94. I didn\rquote t know him we
ll then, and we looked at the worked example, and I remember him saying to me, \'93I\rquote m not quite sure about the degrees of freedom here, whether you\rquote ve really got four degrees of freedom\'94, or whatever it was, and I rather brashly said, 
\'93Well, we must have more than three\'94, and he looked at me with \endash  now I recognise as his teasing look \endash  and said, \'93Oh, so you\rquote re assuming that degrees of freedom are integers, are you?\'94 \'93Yes!\'94 (LAUGHS) I\rquote 
d always assumed that! (LAUGHS) And he was making quite a subtle point about how we\rquote d estimated the maximum likelihood ratio. But it was just a tease! \'85
 So we went ahead with this model, and what was remarkable was that in the same year, two other people, independently, invented it \endash  one a guy in America, and two people in the Netherlands. But we just got in first. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
