\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 No, I don\rquote t. I don\rquote 
t feel proud. I feel pleased that I could do something to push sociology on in the way in which I think it should go. No, I mean, I just enjoyed it. It was a very exciting time. And what I \endash  to be honest, what I feel - if it\rquote 
s a case of feeling proud - what I feel more proud about is the part that I\rquote ve been able to play from a more, if you like, organisational standpoint in European sociology. I was one of the founder editors of the E
uropean Sociological Review, which we had to found because other people in other European countries were having the same difficulty as I felt here, that there weren\rquote t journals that would want our work, or where we would want it to appear. And that
\rquote s now going very well indeed. It\rquote 
s challenging the AJS and the ASR. And then I was one of the people who helped found the European Consortium for Sociological Research, which is going strong still, and bringing together institutions in Europe with similar ideas of
 where sociology should be going, and what it should be like, and we\rquote ve now, I think, over 40 institutions affiliated to the Consortium. And then more recently, I wasn\rquote 
t involved in an organising role, but I was an active participant in two EU networks of Centres of Social Excellence. The first one was called the \'93CHANGEQUAL Network\'94, and there were just six centres in that. And then we followed that up with the 
\'93EQUALSOC Network\'94, where we\rquote d over a dozen Centres. Nuffield was involved in both of these netw
orks. And for me, one of the best things in recent years has being going to the conferences that Equalsoc has organised in different parts of Europe, and seeing, especially, the number of young people coming through and doing the kinds of things that I th
ink they should be doing. And, if anything, more women than men. This idea that somehow, women don\rquote t do quantitative sociology, or they ought to be doing something non-quantitative, well, that\rquote 
s just gone by the board. The one real regret is that British representation at these things has been negligible, and that is just a problem for British sociology. But I just think it\rquote s in very bad shape, and has been for quite a long time. So I
\rquote ve been very lucky in having this official Fellowship at Nuffield. There\rquote s
 no teaching responsibility, no lecturing responsibility, the only teaching responsibility is for graduate students. So it did mean that from 1969 onwards I could work abroad. I never wanted to work abroad for long periods, for family reasons, but I could
 take off for a week or ten days whenever I wanted to, so the original comparative mobility work was done in Stockholm, then the big CASMIN Project was in Mannheim. I was very lucky in the first winter I was here, the winter of early \rquote 
70, I was invited, by 
the British Council, to go on a lecture tour in Germany, talking both about the Affluent Worker project, and then about the work we were planning on mobility, and it was a very difficult time in one way, because it was still all the period of student upri
sings in German universities. But I made some remarkably good friends on that trip, like Walter M\'fcller \endash  that\rquote s when I first Walter M\'fc
ller and Uli Meyer. That has been very important for me, to have these European connections. Because since the mid-seventies, I\rquote ve had very little connection with British sociology. I was editor of Sociology when I first came here \endash  \rquote 
69-\rquote 72 \endash  and I found it increasingly difficult to deal with the BSA Committee, because I followed Michael Banton, who was first editor, and we bo
th put together a Board we thought comprised the people who were doing the most important work in British sociology at the time. There were some very good people there. People at Liverpool still doing industrial sociology, Raymond Illsley in Scotland, doi
n
g very good medical sociology, and I think, if you look at the people who were on the Board at that time, they all did have very well-deserved and well-established reputations. But I was under constant pressure from the BSA Executive to change. We had to 
have so many Marxists, and so many phenomenologists, and so many women, and so many people from Polytechnics. I thought, \'93No, that is not the way to go\'94. So relations became more and more strained, and I didn\rquote 
t want to do a second term as Editor, and I don\rquote 
t suppose I would have been allowed to do so anyway! (LAUGHS) And the same year, or around that same period, I remember going to one or two BSA Conferences, and one on race relations in particular, when nobody seemed to be reporting very much research on 
race relations. It was all going around sniffing each others\rquote  position, whether they were racist or not, and there was all this ideological argument. And that was my last BSA Conference. I stopped subscribing to BSA, and I\rquote 
ve never been a member since then. It\rquote s sad, in a way, but I just didn\rquote t find what was happening in British sociology very appealing, and not intellectually interesting. So I was very fortunate that, you know, I had these European contacts. 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
