\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I suppose in one way the thing abo
ut it was that it did have some theory behind it, and I suppose the thing that gave me a lot of satisfaction there was that it did become the basis of the NS-SEC. It worked out very well. The Committee that they set up with David Lockwood as Chair, and Go
rdon Marshall played quite a big role in that. But, you know, that\rquote s just an instrument. You need these instruments, they\rquote 
re very important but what comes of it sociologically depends how well people use it. But I think some interesting things are coming ou
t from it. The unit within ONS that does health research, have used it to very good effect. We are now using it in our present project, and it\rquote s clear that it is a much better measure of class than even my old schema, because although it\rquote 
s the same theoretical basis, ONS were able to do a lot of research on validating it, and so they\rquote ve implemented the basic theoretical ideas better. That\rquote s showing up in that you get - from our most recent results it seems \endash 
 a stronger association between parental class and children\rquote s class than was shown up before. So it\rquote s the usual story. If you have a better concept, and you operationalise this concept better, you get stronger results.... I mean, it\rquote 
s the old story. If you think about it, if in measuring some concept you have a lot of error in, that will attenuate the relationship. Get rid of some of the error, the relationship comes out in a truer stronger form. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
