\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Has anybody... I mean, are people picking it up and developing it, discussing it, beyond its being reviewed? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh yes. It does get quite a few citations now. And, of course, quite a few of the chapters in it \endash  about a quarter or a third 
\endash  had appeared in journals in earlier versions, and so they have quite good citations. So yes, it is being used. I think what\rquote s happening in European sociology now, or, at least, the European sociology that\rquote 
s represented through the Consortium and these networks, is really very exciting, and in many ways I think there\rquote s more happening and of greater interest than in American sociology. So I\rquote m very optimistic from that point of view, and that
\rquote s where my work, I think, gets most widely cited \endash  people trying to put together some idea of a quantitative sociology which is, at the same tim
e, trying to address major substantive problems, and that requires a theoretical input, where theory is not just for decoration or conceptual elaboration, but really for explanation. I mean, we come up with these - I think in many ways fascinating empiric
al regularities - and then the question is how to explain them. If I can just add, here, something I think is pioneering in this regard, is the work I did with Richard Breen on this model of educational choice, because that\rquote 
s the direction, I think, that th
eory has to go. You have these well-defined regularities, particularly the persistence of social inequalities in educational attainment relating to class background, or ethnic background and why? And the further work that I did in that area, with Robert E
r
ikson, Michelle Jackson, involves this distinction between primary and secondary effects in creating educational inequalities. That is what we were able to show, was that one source of these inequalities is that kids from more advantaged backgrounds just 
perform better in school \endash 
 for a whole lot of reasons one could examine, and we know more and more about. But then, second, over and above that, children from more advantaged backgrounds make more ambitious educational choices, even when you hold prior performance constant. That
\rquote s the crucial thing. What we were able to show was that, on some quite good data, if you hold constant how well people did at \lquote O\rquote  Levels, age 16, the probabilities of going on, then, to \lquote A\rquote  Levels \endash 
 in other words, taking the exams you need to get into university \endash  are very strongly influenced by social background, even for kids who performed at the same level at \lquote O\rquote 
 Level. And so this, I think, exemplifies what (TROUBLE WITH MICROPHONE) I\rquote m interested in: that you use the statistical analysis to reveal the correct structure of the regularities you\rquote 
re interested in, and then that sets up an explanatory problem. You can\rquote t use statistics to crank out some explanation - that\rquote s where the creative thinking comes in. You\rquote ve got to come up wi
th some kind of model of what is going on here at the level of individual action and interaction, and then, again, you can come back to statistics, or, perhaps, other kind of data, to try and test that model to see whether it works. And so that\rquote 
s what Breen and I did with this so-called \'93relative risk aversion\'94 model of educational choice. And what\rquote s been very satisfying is that there\rquote 
s now a very big body of literature trying to test this model, and I reviewed it as it was up to 2007, in one chapter in the second edition of my book. And there\rquote 
s been a lot done since, and more sophisticated research. And there are some problems with the model, but people are trying to develop it. But by and large it works fairly well. So that\rquote s the kind of sociology that I w
ould just like to see more of. I think it is happening. There\rquote s been a movement in sociology. It was developed quite a bit in Nuffield in the last ten years in one version, by people like Peter Hedstr\'f6m, who\rquote s now gone back to Sweden 
\endash  mechanism-based theorising... I mean, it\rquote s getting away from the old idea that causal explanation has to be done by reference to some kind of covering law: you subsume things under some general covering law which, I don\rquote 
t think, ever worked in sociology! And the idea now is, no, you\rquote ve got to try and establish the mechanism. What are the processes actually going on that link the supposed cause to the effect you\rquote re interested in? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So would you be willing to go so far as to say that there are certain already advantaged ho
useholds in which children are taught to think ambitiously? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 That\rquote s part of it. But to elaborate on that, the idea is that the first concern of most parents is to avoid downward mobility 
\endash  we put it in that way \endash  and there is some good psychological theory for that, what Kahneman, who also won the Nobel Prize, calls \'93prospect theory\'94, that you\rquote 
re more worried about losses than gains. That you would be more worried if you lost \'a35 than [pleased] if you found a \'a35 note in the gutter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So is this why you used the economics expression \endash  \'93risk aversion\'94? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Although what we say is, it\rquote 
s relative. So all families, we suppose, want to avoid downward mobility. And then as a second priority, to be upwardly mobile. Now, in the case of more advan
taged families, these two things more or less go together. They know - if the parents are high level professionals/managers - they know it\rquote 
s important if their kids are going to maintain their position, that they get higher education. So they will push them into higher education, even if their results aren\rquote t all that great. It\rquote s in the middle range of performance at \lquote O
\rquote  Level, that you find the biggest class differences in who goes on. The very, very bright kids go on, whatever their class origins, and the very, very stupid ones don\rquote t \endash  \'93bright\'94 and \'93stupid\'94
 in terms of past performance. But in the middle, you\rquote ll find children from more advantaged backgrounds being pushed to go on, with \lquote O\rquote  Level results that, in the case of somebody from a working-class bac
kground, they would never think of going on. But for people from less advantaged backgrounds there can be a dilemma, because the best way of not being downwardly mobile, if you\rquote 
re a skilled manual worker, or lower level technician, would be to do something similar. You\rquote 
ve got a reasonably good performance, so, okay, take an apprenticeship, go and take some vocational training. If you want to be upwardly mobile, and want to aim to do \lquote A\rquote  Levels and go on to university, well, there\rquote 
s a risk then, because you might not make it. Then you might be even worse off than if you\rquote d never tried - now, especially with the cost of this - and you might have missed some other opportunity for an apprenticeship you can\rquote 
t go back to. This is the basic idea, that the choices are more difficult for people, as it were, not in the most advantaged positions. So there you do find a lot of kids with \lquote O\rquote  Level results which, if they\rquote 
d been obtained by a kid from a more advantaged background, would mean they would be certain to go on to do \lquote A\rquote  Levels, but in some cases they don\rquote t. And so again, it\rquote s this idea that you\rquote 
ve to do a detailed analysis of the empirical data, to find out just what the regularities are, and then you\rquote ve to come up with some explanatory model for what is it that\rquote s generating these regularities. Especially if \endash 
 as in this case \endash  we could show they change very little from the 1970s through to the beginning of this century. Of course, we did finally put this model in a mathematical form, as the economists do, and there are pros and cons for that. I wouldn
\rquote t say it\rquote s necessary always to formalise these models, but there are some advantages, because some people have found implications of our model through looking at the mathematics that, actually, we weren\rquote t aware of \endash  and that
\rquote s quite interesting! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 In other words, implications for which you need to develop further explanations. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, no, no, more information that give you opportunity for empirical tests. That\rquote 
s the important thing, look what the implications are. And there\rquote s a good argument for saying that the more testable implications an explanatory model has, the better. There\rquote 
s a famous case reported by several authors. R.A. Fisher, the great statistician, was once asked, \'93How could people doing observational, as opposed to experimental studies, make their theories more testable?\'94 He said, \'93Make them more elaborate
\'94, which seems a bit odd at first, because you usually think simplicity in a theory is a good thing. But what he meant was, if they\rquote re more elaborate, then there\rquote 
ll be more opportunities for testing them. He comes back, if you like, to my old arguments with Norbert Elias. I never could get him to answer the question, \'93Norbert, what would I have to s
how, empirically, to make you believe that your theories were wrong?\'94
 I have this same problem today with the Bourdieusians who I think, to be frank, are a blight on British sociology. I think the effects of Bourdieu have just been overwhelmingly negative. And it\rquote 
s always the problem when you do some research and say, \'93This doesn\rquote t seem consistent with Bourdieu\rquote s position\'94, \'93Oh, Bourdieu didn\rquote t say that, he said something else\'94, and it\rquote s always something else. It\rquote 
s like trying to nail jelly to the wall! So I end up saying, \'93Well, please give me a statement of one of Bourdieu\rquote s theories and then tell me what I would have to show, empirically, to make you believe that this theory was wrong\'94
. You can never get a clear answer. So, if a theory can\rquote t be tested in this way, can\rquote t be shown to be wrong, I don\rquote t see how it can contain any information. It has to be saying that something can\rquote t be the case, so it\rquote 
s testable. And if you can\rquote t test it, then what is it actually saying? And this is the problem that I always have with a lot of this so-called social theory. Is it trying to offer testable explanations? If so, it\rquote 
s not clear what they are. Is it just playing around with concepts? Well, okay, it may be useful or not \endash  it depends how illuminating the concepts turn out to be. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
