\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes, I was saying that this work with Tak Wing Chan on cultural consumption brought me back to this
 concern with the distinction between class and status, which, of course, played a role in the Affluent Worker project. This has really now taken off in a number of different fields, because, at the same time, Robert Erikson, working with other people in 
S
tockholm, was very interested in health inequalities. What we both together worked towards was this idea we should get away from one-dimensional conceptions of social stratification, and think more consistently in a multi-dimensional way, and distinguish 
between two different relational aspects of stratification \endash  class and status \endash  and then what we call two different \'93attributional aspects\'94 \endash 
 income and education. The attributional ones are where you just have more or less of a certain thing \endash  income/educa
tion. The relational ones are where the inequalities inhere in social relationships of some kind. What we found in the cultural consumption study was that patterns of cultural consumption are not all that strongly associated with social class but rather w
ith social status, and not so much with income but with education. And then Tak Wing and I did one of the most important papers I\rquote 
ve done in recent years, in the ASR, on this distinction between class and status. We applied it in other areas, and one of the
 most striking ones was in regard to socio-political attitudes. If you look at Left/Right attitudes, these are overwhelmingly structured by class, and status plays little part. If you look at Liberterian/Authoritarian attitudes, they are structured by sta
tus, and class plays little part. In one of the projects that I\rquote 
m now working on with Bess Bukodi, we are looking at the effects of social origins on educational attainment, but again breaking social origins down into parental class, parental status, and pa
rental education, and where we can, parental income. What we find is that with all these different aspects, each of these different aspects of social origin, there\rquote s a separate and independent effect on children\rquote 
s educational attainment. You can\rquote t use them as somehow interchangeable indicators of one single underlying stratification dimension, you need a more differentiated approach. What\rquote 
s also interesting is that over time the relative importance seems to be changing. Class is pretty constant - the effect
s of parental class are pretty constant. Effects of parental status seem to be declining, but effects of parental education seem to be increasing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, we\rquote ve now got generations where grandmothers have gone to university. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
