\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 It sounds dangerous. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 

\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Not as much as it might seem at first sight. What you can say is that it\rquote 
s less dangerous than proceeding on the basis of just the data you have. Because unless you can assume that the missing data is missing at random, which we know, for sure, it\rquote 
s not, then there are two arguments. One, you can just work with the complete cases, only the complete cases, knowing that the missing cases will not be missing at random, or you can try and impute missing data. You don\rquote t do it once, it\rquote 
s called \'93multiple imputation\'94. You create maybe five or six different imputed data sets in different ways, and then you take an average value. So far there are no big differences in the results. Yo
u reduce the standard errors in the imputed data. But we\rquote ll see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So, in other words, it\rquote s almost like saying it\rquote s better to do that than not at all. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
