\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, we were very lucky. We had two children, and compared with, you know
, a lot of our contemporaries, I have to say they were remarkably trouble-free children. They both went to the local comp, it was a good comp, as you might imagine, in North Oxford, but before comprehensivisation it was a secondary modern, and it kept the
 same Headmaster, and when we first came here, and people said, \'93Oh, this is terrible!\'94, and \'93This man was only Headmaster of the secondary modern\'94. And a lot of people wouldn\rquote 
t send their children there, they went private. But I went round the school. He seemed to run a very tight ship, seemed a sensible guy. They brought a lot of new teachers in, of course, when they had to do \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels. Excellent teachers. My daughter was taught English by Philip Pullman, and my son, and they\rquote re still friends. So they bo
th went to Cambridge. My daughter did Natural Sciences, and a Ph.D. in virology, and my son did English, and then did a Ph.D. at the Open University in English \endash  Daniel Defoe studies. My daughter she didn\rquote 
t like lab life, so she worked for a kind of scient
ific publishing company, and they attended conferences, did any kind of scientific writing. But then she met a guy, a German guy, who was also a virologist. She had a singing career as well - my wife was a professional singer as well as an academic 
\endash  and m
y daughter wanted to do this, and had support in Germany from the Munich Wagnerverein, a stipendium at Bayreuth. But then when she was pregnant for the first time, third trimester, something unfortunate happened. She got this severe version of Bell
\rquote s Palsy, and some facial paralysis, and that really stopped her singing career just as it was taking off. She still does sing as well - some professional engagements - but more locally in Munich, mainly for church music. But she\rquote 
s a Hausfrau and seems to be quite enjoying it, so we\rquote ve two Bavarian grandchildren. My son struck lucky, he didn\rquote 
t know what to do with his Ph.D. in English, and he was thinking of going and doing a Diploma in Education, but he had a girlfriend who worked at Sotheby\rquote s, just as an administrator. He\rquote 
d always [been] interested in rare books and things, and a job came up in the Rare Books Department. They don\rquote t advertise, they only tell their staff, they just use networking - again, sheer chance - and he went in for it, he got it, and he\rquote 
s now Senior Director in the Rare Books Department at Sotheby\rquote s, and he\rquote s been there for, 10, 15 years now. He\rquote s finding it a bit stressful \endash 
 the business side, and some really appalling people it seems he has to deal with. But he\rquote s got the record, at the moment, for the highest value of a book at a sale that he organised, for Audibon\rquote s Birds of America, which fetched nearly \'a3
6 million. So family life, from that point of view, has been remarkably smooth. The only thing is, of course, that half of our family lives in Germany. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
