\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Of course, he\rquote s got exactly well, the right - obviously would have - accent to read that poem \endash 
 the way he imagined it, I suppose, with the short a\rquote s. It was so funny when my daughter was a pupil of Philip Pullman\rquote s, they\rquote d to read Blake\rquote s, The Tiger, and I\rquote 
d already read that quite a bit with my daughter, and when she read it, she read it with short a\rquote s, things like \'93grasp\'94 and \'93clasp\'94, and Pullman said afterwards, \'93Sian, that\rquote s interesting. Why did you use short a\rquote s?\'94
 She looked at him, \'93Oh well, you know, my father\rquote s from Yorkshire, and I read it first with him.\'94 And Pullman said, \'93I\rquote ve never thought about it, but it sounds better. I wonder how Blake pronounced it?\'94 (LAUGHS) No, we\rquote 
ll never know! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
