\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Well, I mean, my two closest friends, I suppose, professionally and in any other way \endash  one certainly Robert Erikson. We
\rquote ve worked together. This May we celebrate our 40th anniversary. (LAUGHS) He\rquote s been a very close friend, close colleague. And then Walter M\'fcller. So they were both close friends and close colleagues. The other thing we haven\rquote 
t mentioned \endash  something else I\rquote m quite proud about actually \endash  is the number of really good graduate students that I\rquote ve had. I was just thinking about it, and I wrote a list here \endash  and I\rquote m sure I\rquote 
ve forgotten some \endash 
 but there are about 20. All of whom have had really quite successful academic careers as sociologists, and now some of them retiring, which is a bit scary! I mean, John Child at Cambridge; Anthony Heath when he was at Cambridge; Graham Salaman who we
nt to Open University; Geoff Ingham, who stayed in Cambridge \endash  just retired. Duncan Gallie, here, who\rquote 
s coming up to retiring. Jose-Maria Maraval, who became Minister of Education in Spain and then Professor at the Juan Mach Institute in Madrid \endash  also retiring. Colin Crouch, who has retired; Susan McRae, who has retired; Niamh Hardiman, who\rquote 
s still going strong in Dublin; Geoff Evans, who\rquote s here; Gordon Marshall, of course, went off to ESRC, and then is now head of Leverhulme; Debbie Posel, she\rquote s now Professor at Witswatersrand; Colin Mills, who\rquote 
s here; Sawako Shirahase, who\rquote s just become the first ever woman Professor of Sociology in Tokyo University, which is the male bastion!; Tak Wing Chan who\rquote s here, of course. Brendan Halpin, who is at Limerick; and la
st in was Michelle Jackson who married David Grusky, and she is in Stanford. So of course, a lot of these became friends as well as students. So I don\rquote t think there were many friends outside of academic life, who had any influence, except one 
\endash  a remarkabl
e man called Nils Taube. He was born in Estonia, a son of the German Baron von Taube, part of this German aristocracy that ruled in the Baltic countries. They were called back by Hitler to Germany - well, they had to really move back. It was the end of th
e
 War. His father died on the way back, trying to get from Estonia into Germany. He and his mother survived. His mother had some English family connections, and so they managed to get to England with not very much money, but some connections. Nils was a te
e
nager at that time. He missed out on university. They traditionally went to Tartu University - in the old days it was called Dortpat when it was a German university. But then he went into the City, did a few classes on finance or something, at what used t
o be Regent Street Poly, went into a City firm of stockbrokers. I met him in Cambridge at a party in the sixties sometime, and we became good friends \endash  two couples \endash 
 and we played a bit of tennis together, and we kept in touch. Then he had a spectacular car
eer. He became one of the most successful stockbrokers; and then he went to work for Rothschild, and one of the most successful investors. And there is a book on the twelve most successful investors, and he\rquote 
s in there with Warren Buffet and so on. And he w
as a remarkable man, because he did it all as a kind of game. How much money you made was just a measure of how well you were doing in the game. He lived in a very nice house in Essex, and one in Hampstead, but his own tastes were very simple. He just lik
ed playing this game. He died, unfortunately, three or four years ago, but he had a big influence on me, just as a person, and the way in which he viewed life. In a way, he was a bit of an academic manqu\'e9
, and so we talked about a very wide range of things. There\rquote s interestingly a connection with somebody I think you\rquote ve already interviewed. Ray Pahl\rquote s daughter married one of Nil\rquote 
s sons... So each summer, the Taubes used to have a big garden party at this house in Essex, near Wivenhoe, [was it at Gt. Wigborou
gh? Yes!], not far away, and I used to see Ray there sometimes. Because it was a lot of champagne and quails eggs, and then we used to play tennis. It was very funny tennis! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
