\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 No, what I didn\rquote t say, I think. I had this project with Wing, and I had to be called
 the Research Assistant then, because it was the only way they could get this through the University, until the RAE came around. Then they realised that they couldn\rquote 
t put me in for this if I was in such a lowly position. I got paid a part-time professorial
 salary, on the assumption that I was working, was it 60 hours a week as a Research Assistant? It was some ridiculous fiddle to get round absurd bureaucracy in this University. Then that finished, and I had an honorary position at the Institute of Educati
on, where Bess was working. We put together this big project, submitted it to the ESRC, and we got it. About the same time Bess got a job in Oxford, in the Social Policy Department, with a Fellowship at Nuffield, so we had to \'93migrate\'94
, as they call it, the project to Oxford. And the University, of course, were very pleased to accept it \endash  big overheads and so on. Then it came to my appointment, because, I, again, had a 20% time in this project. Oh, I couldn\rquote 
t be appointed, I was too old! The University had just brought in something called the \'93Employer\rquote s Justifiable Retirement Age\'94 \endash  it\rquote 
s to get round the EU regulations, whatever. So I was turned down. And well, of course, the Head of the Department \endash  Social Policy Department \endash  was furious about this, and poi
nted out that they had accepted the grant, and all my details were in there, and so it went back a second time, and apparently there was a big argument, because I was the first special case under this new dispensation, so they wanted to be tough. And some
body apparently said, \'93This is not so much a return from retirement, as a resurrection!\'94 (LAUGHS) To which I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m in good company anyway!\'94 But in the end they gave way. So I am, I\rquote 
m told, the oldest person ever to be appointed in this University, apart from possibly some mediaeval friar as well! (LAUGHS) So I took a title, and I\rquote m called, \'93Distinguished Senior Research Fellow\'94, and it\rquote 
s for three years, starting last April - for the duration of the grant. So I\rquote m still in gainful employment, and I don\rquote t think I shall retire. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
