\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
I think that is a distinct possibility. Yes, because, you see something, not exactly the same, but similar, has been happening in political science here \endash  that\rquote s become more quantitative. So there
 are a lot of people here - well, Geoff Evans has been a major influence in Oxford, so that is an obvious linkage there. And, of course, the other thing that\rquote s cheered me enormously \endash 
 I was very doubtful, five years ago, what was really going to happen to sociology in Oxford and in Nuffield, because there were one or two not very encouraging developments, but that\rquote 
s been totally transformed. We were incredibly lucky. When Anthony Heath retired, and Jay Gershuny retired through ill-heath, we advertised the s
enior Chair, and out of the blue, we got Francesco Billari, who is the top European demographer, but very much a social demographer, and very knowledgeable. It was just an incredible stroke of luck. Nobody thought that he would, but he was keen to come to
 Oxford, and then we got Janne Jonsson, coming as an official Fellow. We\rquote ve another Chair to fill, that Nuffield will fund. And we\rquote ve got a new demography post that\rquote 
s coming with Francesco, so the last couple of years things have really changed so much for the better here. At last we\rquote ve got really good leadership in the Sociology Department, so that\rquote 
s encouraging. So a more upbeat note to finish on! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
