\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
That should be fine. So this is the second interview done by Anne Murcott with John Goldthorpe, at Nuffield College, on Friday, November 8th, 2013. I\rquote m really grateful, John, thank you for letting me come back. I have to say, I don\rquote t k
now if I said to you last time, but I hugely enjoyed the conversation, it was like having a private seminar. It was absolutely wonderful! I went away walking on air! (LAUGHS) And I went away with one question of mine that I was kicking myself I\rquote 
d never asked you, and I don\rquote t know whether you\rquote ll think it\rquote s banal or a trite question, but it\rquote 
s one that struck me in listening to you talk about particularly your early childhood and your family, did you ever go underground yourself? Were you ever down a pit? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Oh yes! Not while I was a child. I think I went once when I was a young teenager, just down to the pit bottom. But when I was doing my Ph.D. research, that was on mining, so I went down the colliery where my father worked \endash 
 the next village to where I grew up \endash 
 several times, to go and look at conditions on the face. Because what I was interested in was the way in which different technological systems of mining affected relations between the miners and their immediate supervisors. At that time I was als
o at University of Leicester, so I did the same thing at another pit near Leicester \endash  there\rquote s a coalfield near to Leicester, a pit called Snibston \endash 
 so I went down there. And in the local pit, I was, of course, given a pretty hard time, because some of the miners were people I\rquote 
d grown up with, and of course, they took me in all the worst places. I mean, going through a three-foot-six seam, where you really just more or less had to semi-crawl. And then, of course, you get, if you\rquote re not careful, what they call \'93miner
\rquote s buttons\'94, and this is on your spine. You get the top skinned off, and you get a scab on the top if you\rquote re not careful, and it\rquote s really painful! (LAUGHS) So it\rquote 
s like a row of buttons down the back of your spine! (LAUGHS) And [they\rquote re] telling me, \'93Oh, this is where old so and so got killed\'94, and \'93So and so had a terrible accident here\'94
. Then they take you into a place where the ground is what they call \'93working\'94, and you saw these - in those days, of course, they were hydraulic props, before they would have been wooden - you\rquote ll see the prop just moving, you\rquote 
ll see as if the ground is breathing. But fortunately, at that time, I was pretty fit, because I was playing a lot of tennis! It was really exhausting, going down there. And they do all these tricks. They\rquote 
re telling you to turn your lamp off on your head, and they turn theirs off, and the darkness is unbelievable, because normally when you go into a dark room, you wait a few seconds, and your eyes adjust \endash  there is some light. But down there 
\endash  the mine \endash  with the lights out, there is no light at all, and it\rquote 
s just total blackness. It really is. But it was quite fascinating. I did have a minor accident, oddly enough. I got too near a coal cutting machine, and the spray got me, and I\rquote ve been a bit
 deaf ever since! I lost quite a lot of hearing in one ear, in the cause of industrial sociology! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I\rquote m just going to move my chair slightly, because I\rquote m looking at you a bit sideways. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
