\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Yes. Well, I can. Yes. It was a man called Geoffrey Richardson, who taught me French and German in the sixth form. He was an inspirational teacher. He did, in fact, go on to be a Lecturer in ed
ucation, and we were colleagues again at Leicester, strangely enough. And then he went on to Hull, and I think stayed there. I believe he died fairly recently. And what I got from Richardson - he was like a great educational force as it were. My parents w
ere always very supportive of me, so far as education was concerned, but one would have to say that their view of education was very instrumental. This is the way you got a good job. So this is where the encouragement came from. They obviously didn
\rquote t want m
e to end up in the pit, doing, I suppose, manual work. As I told you before, my father was a clerk at the mine, and they were obviously hoping perhaps for something better for me, so education was the way to that. And I suppose I took over this instrument
al view: that you had to go to school, work hard, try hard, because that way you\rquote 
d get a better job. And I think it was only when I got into the sixth form, and with Richardson, that I realised that there was a whole lot more to it than that! You know, open
ing up to one that literature, in particular, was exciting, and he taught it in a historical way. I was doing history at the same time, but we were doing with him, I think the first term, French romantic poetry and drama, in the classroom \endash 
 he was a wonderful actor himself - re-enacting Hugo\rquote 
s Hernanie, and things like that. And you suddenly [realised this was a] tremendously exciting and a wonderful way of communicating. I always remember one thing that he told me that had a very striking effect on me. In the war, he\rquote 
d been in Bomber Command, he was a gunner, I think a tail gunner, which was one of the most dangerous things. And he once told me that whenever he went on a bombing raid over Germany, he took a volume of Heine\rquote s poetry in his flack jacket, just
 to remind him that there was another Germany. And I just suddenly saw why literature was so important, and that somebody could think of that when they\rquote re going bombing Germany. \'93I must take Heine\rquote s poetry with me!\'94
 So he was quite inspirational. Really inspirational. And so that was the big impact. And things just changed from there. What I\rquote m doing here is not just a ticket to a better job, it\rquote s important and exciting and valuable in itself \endash 
 that was the big change. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Paul\rquote s question has \'93teachers\'94 in the plural. Once you\rquote 
d had that sort of awakening did other teachers respond differently to you, and did you suddenly see them as more inspirational? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 [It was] probably more a case that I responded differently to them. I did have really good teac
hers in the sixth form. My grammar school was one of the schools, grammar schools, that was started in mining areas in the inter-war years. It was very difficult, at that time, I think, for teachers to get jobs, so they were able to recruit some very good
 people who were, then, obviously, you know, perhaps in their fifties and so on by the time I got there \endash  coming to the end of their time. But I did have really very good teachers. The other teachers didn\rquote 
t have this, as it were, inspirational quality of Richardson, but they were really passionate. I always thought \endash  thinking back about them \endash  I remember, somebody said about John Wesley that \'93he preached as a dying man to dying men\'94
, and they taught like that. It was really, really important, and they were t
otally committed, and you felt it mattered enormously to them as well as to you, and I thought that that was very good. I never had the problems that Jackson and Marsden talked about in their book, of somebody from a working-class/lower-middle-class home 
g
oing to a traditional middle-class grammar school. Because the great thing was these schools were in the mining areas. The middle-classes were very thin on the ground, so the majority of kids there were from similar backgrounds to myself, so that there wa
sn\rquote t this kind of problem, and the teachers knew that. In many ways, I think they saw it as their mission, that they had a mission to \endash  maybe putting it a bit harshly \endash 
 take you away from your family and your community into what they saw as a wider world. So I had always a very different view on grammar schools to the Jackson and Marsden one! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, that was very urban, wasn\rquote t it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 And these schools, they were promoted, at that time, by a remarkable Director of Education for the West R
iding, called A.B. Clegg. There\rquote s a man called H.E. Dent, who used to write books on the history of education - \lquote 40s and \lquote 50s - and he talked about \'93Clegg\rquote s Children\'94
, and these were the kids from these areas in South Yorkshire, predominantly working-class, lower-middle-class, who went to these grammar schools. There was Wath, one near Rotherham, some over more to the east \endash 
 Thorne and Goole, the old little dockland areas down there on the Humber; and Mexborough was the neighbouring school, that\rquote s a slightl
y longer history, but it was in this group. There were these five schools, I forget the name of the one near Rotherham now \endash 
and I think they did have a very distinctive culture. They were predominantly working-class/lower-middle-class grammar schools. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
