\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Great! Thank you. I think this is the professional historian\rquote s question, isn\rquote 
t it! (LAUGHS) Your best known early article argues for the importance of history in social research, and he asks how far do you still hold this view? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Well, my vi
ews on the relationship between history and sociology have certainly changed. That early article, early 1960s, was a bit of a reaction against what, at the time, I saw as being a very ahistorical nature of a lot of American sociology of the day. I mean, o
n the one hand, Parsons\rquote  abstract system - social system - theory, and on the other hand the kind of survey research that was very much oriented towards attitudes. I did feel that both these approaches \endash  the theoretical and the empirical 
\endash  really paid very 
little regard to historical context. So that was behind that paper. But I did write, actually I think early 1972, a postscript to that paper, which is in this book, edited by Martin Bulmer, Sociological Research Methods. He reprinted the original paper, b
ut I wrote a postscript because, at around that time \endash  early seventies \endash  my views were changing, and, really, in reaction to what I called, in a later paper, \'93grand historical sociology\'94
, a kind of thing that, I suppose, starting with [Shmuel] Eisenstadt\rquote s sociology of empires, and then very influential, Barrington-Moore\rquote s work. Then also, Theda Skocpol on revolutions, Perry Anderson\rquote 
s work, and then after that, Michael Mann, I really felt that what this work showed was that these people did not understand, 
or did not want to understand, how history was actually written. And this coming from my original training as a historian, in a very professional history school at UCL, where we were always taught [methodology] - we had a kind of catechism, you know, one 
of the first questions, \'93What is the nature of historical fact?\'94 And the answer was, you know, \'93A historical fact is an inference from the relics\'94. You only write history from what\rquote s left from the past, whether it\rquote 
s bones or pots, most commonly, of course, 
documents of one kind or another, and you always have to link it to that: and the idea that the inferences that you draw from the relics, arer generally rather problematic and tenuous, need a great deal of care in interpretation, and always open to revisi
on and so on. And then I found these people, ironically, since they were often represented as part of the reaction against positivism in sociology, taking what I\rquote 
d been taught was an extremely positivist view of historiography: that the facts are there - wh
ere will we find little entities that you could collect from secondary, tertiary sources, and use as the building bricks of these grand sociological schemes. I was really shocked when I read Barrington-Moore, about what seemed to be the very low quality o
f
 his understanding of, for example, the history of the English Civil War. He just seemed to take whatever interpretation of this, or the French Revolution, that suited his general argument, and neglect the rest. One of my teachers at UCL, on French histor
y, had been Alfred Cobham, who was one of the originators of the revisionist history of the French Revolution, along with Furet, and to me, Barrington-Moore was somewhere way back in the past! He just didn\rquote 
t know what had happened to the historiography of the French Revolution! So I did have a big reaction against that kind of grand historical sociology. I didn\rquote 
t think it was doing any favours to history or to sociology. Then more recently, as I worked more and more in comparative sociology - in comparative studies of social mobility, for example - I\rquote 
ve come to view something on these lines. I was very influenced by a book, it came out somewhere, I think, in the seventies, by Przeworski and Teune, on comparative sociology. And their programme was that you sho
uld try to replace the names of nations with the names of variables, and the idea was that it doesn\rquote t help very much if you say, to take a medical example Japan has much lower rates of premature death from heart disease than America. That doesn
\rquote t tell you very much. So you\rquote ve to try and replace \'93Japan\'94 and \'93America\'94, with some relevant variable, like consumption of saturated fat, and then you\rquote re getting somewhere. That\rquote s what really matters. You\rquote 
ve to say why, what is it about America or Japan that is relev
ant to this? So when we were doing our comparative mobility research, if we were trying to explain cross-national differences in the rates of mobility, we had to look for some variables that we could put the countries on, not just say, \'93
Well, Germany is different\'94, \'93England is different from the Netherlands\'94, \'93Japan is different\'94 - that\rquote 
s not very informative. So we had to look at things like, for example, things like degree of income inequality, differences in distribution of education. Well, let\rquote s put these variables in - and that\rquote 
s what I think sociologists should try to do. But then, at the same time, you have to recognise that this Przeworski-Teune programme has limits, and you come to a point where it really is the case that let\rquote s say, \'93Germany is just Germany. It
\rquote s different. There\rquote s something about the German educational system that is specifically German\'94, and the only way you could make that into a variable, would be to score Germany 1 and all the others 0! (LAUGHS) It\rquote 
s not very informative! So in this way, I think, I see this as the borderline between sociology and history, and at some point, the Przeworski-Teune programme comes up against the buffers, and you have to say, \'93
Yes, there were certain things in German history, and development of German culture, which just meant they ended up with an educational training system that was really very different from anywhere else\'94. And that\rquote 
s really all you could say - just something very specific, unique to Germany. And again, you will look at a country li
ke Hungary, and you find differences there, which you cannot treat in terms of variables, they just reflect the fact that after the First World War, Hungary was chopped down enormously in size, then it had a highly autocratic regime, then a Communist regi
m
e, but more recently moved back again to capitalism. These are just specific features of Hungarian society, and even under communism there was some very distinctive features of Hungarian society that made it a very different communist society from, say, P
o
lish society. So in some ways, I see, now, history as a limiting factor for sociology: that sometimes you have to appeal to history, yeah, that the explanation is historical, but I still see a clear distinction between historical explanations and sociolog
ical explanations. I don\rquote t think we\rquote d gain much by going down the Philip Abrams\rquote  and Tony Giddens\rquote  route, saying, \'93these are essentially the same subject\'94. I just don\rquote 
t think that works. And I think that if Abrams and Giddens had done more empirical comparative research, they might have come to that conclusion themselves! (LAUGHS) That\rquote s how my views have changed! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Can I just take you back to make sure I\rquote ve understood what you\rquote 
ve just said. Can you enlarge, slightly, on the distinction between historical explanation on the one hand, and sociological explanation on the other. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Yes. Okay. Well, I think sociologists do want to aim at some kind of generality in explanation, and going back to the example of social mobility, when we found, in The Cons
tant Flux, that there were some very marked similarities in mobility, and especially in patterns of relative mobility across different modern societies, as a sociologist, I felt that was an interesting finding. And then, since you have these generalities 
across time and space, you need an explanation that is similarly general \endash 
 it may not be totally universal, but the more your explanations can apply across time and space, in a way, as a sociologist, the more satisfied you are. Historical explanations, I th
ink, are different. They are explanations of specificities, where what you want to do is to show how a particular situation arose as a result of a concatenation of a whole series of previous events that led up to it, and these events may be very specific.
 They may involve sheer chance. I mean, look at it this way, I\rquote ve just been writing something on this about the sociology of revolutions - whether you can have a sociology of revolutions, and I don\rquote 
t really think you can. Because when you look at particular cases of revolution, there aren\rquote 
t sufficient empirical regularities in these cases to allow for any kind of general explanation. They all do seem to be so different from each other, and often the role of chance events in them, strikes me as being very imp
ortant, so that you really do need a very place and time specific explanation of the whole concatenation of events leading up to that particular outcome. So that\rquote s really the difference. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 So you\rquote re saying that you can only explain revolution in historical terms, a sociological explanation won\rquote t work? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. I mean, if you\rquote 
re looking, say, for example, for these cross-national and over time regularities that we found in mobility patterns, historical explanation wouldn\rquote 
t really be adequate there because a historical explanation would have to be about what happened here at this time, and there at that time - but we say, no, this is more general. So you\rquote 
ve to come up with an explanation that can, in a way, transcend national, cultural, and institutional peculiarities, because what you\rquote 
re trying to explain extends across these, so the explanation has to be put in some more general terms. We try to do it in terms of the way in which \endash  to put it very simply \endash  inequalities of c
ondition have a powerful effect on inequalities of opportunity, and this is something that holds good in say, Japan, as in this country. I always remember, when giving a seminar at the Nippon Centre here, at St. Antony\rquote 
s - the Japanese Study Centre. People there were mainly anthropologists and historians, [and they] were very worried about the class concept that we used \endash  the same for Britain and Japan \endash  and they said, \'93
But social class means something completely different in Japan. It\rquote s not the same as in England. You can\rquote t use the same conceptual scheme\'94. And - I had a Japanese colleague - our reply was, \'93
Well, yes, we realise that attitudes and beliefs about social class are different in Britain and Japan. But in a way, we don\rquote t care. What we show is, tha
t when we use the same conceptual scheme in Britain and Japan, we get remarkably similar results\'94. So, \'93This is the fact - you\rquote 
ve got to take on board that even though people may think about social class differently in Japan to the way they do in Britain, it still is the case that there are these very strong empirical regularities. In this respect, it\rquote 
s the similarities between the societies that\rquote s striking, and not the differences\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Is that taking us back to a distinction with which I was brought up, that Weber makes between \'93class\'94 and \'93status\'94
? And that, somehow, your conceptual schema was getting closer to class, which can be argued to be independent of how people allocate status positions? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Oh! Yes. Our understanding of class relatio
ns is grounded in relations in labour markets and production units, and a lot was made of the different Japanese system of employment relations. We did recognise that. But it turned out that that had very little effect on Japanese mobility patterns. The c
h
ances of mobility, say, for manual wage workers in Japan, relative to those of salaried professionals and managers, is essentially the same as in Britain. Now these things may have been - as you say - have been interpreted in Japanese society in a quite d
ifferent way. That may well be so. We don\rquote t know too much about that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 But it\rquote s studiable. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Absolutely. Now, there is a lot of work going on in Japan, by Japanese sociologists, who are very much in reaction against the earlier, more anthropological literature that said, \'93Japan is different. Japan is unique\'94
. But coming back to the point, I think that all societies are different, unique in some particulars, but then one shouldn\rquote t ignore the commonalities. That\rquote s really the heart of the matter. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
