\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
What I also wanted to say was that I am very much in favour of, if I can put it, a different kind of historical sociology to that represented by Eisenstadt, Barrington-Moore, Scokpol, and this is where for, as it were, good social scientific reasons, it
\rquote s important to study a historical situation. I\rquote ll give you two examples from my graduate students. Michael Anderson\rquote s book on family structure in Lancashire during the Industrial Revolution - if you want to tackle
 a very important sociological question about the effect of industrialisation, and specifically the factory system, on family structure, yeah, you have to go back. And, of course, what Anderson used, as a good historian - sociologist in origin - were the 
primary materials, and what he did I would regard as serious historiography. Then again, my student, Gordon Marshall, did this wonderful book on the Weber thesis in Scotland. I mean, okay, the Scots had a lot of Calvinism, they didn\rquote 
t have very much capital
ism in the 17th and 18th centuries - why? And again, young Marshall went back to the basic sources, the basic sources on the development of large-scale capitalist enterprise in Scotland, and then all material on the teaching of Calvinist divines. So in fa
ct, while I\rquote ve been in Nuffield, I guess I\rquote ve had a part in supervising probably more theses in historical sociology than just about any other sociologist, because we\rquote 
ve always taken social historians in Nuffield - fairly modern social historians - and we\rquote ve always had a Professor or Reader in Economic and Social History, who then tended to be these students\rquote 
 University supervisor, but we always had a system in Nuffield of having a College supervisor as well. So for these historians, I usually acted as the supplementary College Supervisor. We had some, I mean, wonderful people, now very eminent \endash 
 Tom Lacqueur, Rick Trainor, Lucia Zedner, and I was their College supervisor the whole time. And that I enjoyed very much, because these were serious historians, gra
ppling with the primary sources. And Richard Whiting did a wonderful book on the origins of Cowley, with the coming of Morris. So I kept very much in touch with what was going on in modern history in that way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
