No. You know, the kind of school of history I was brought up in, did place some very strong emphasis on professional technique. We used to be taken by Jimmy Neale, our professor
 - great expert on Elizabethan times - to the Public Record Office. He would take a document and say, \'93Now, look, this is what we have to work with\'94, and, you know, \'93the first question you ask is, \lquote 
Who produced this document? Where did it come from? Why? Why was it produced?\rquote  And you interrogate it. [He would] show you all the mistakes you might make. Now, it says here, \lquote This\rquote , but actually, that\rquote s misleading. That
\rquote s not where you\rquote ve to look, you\rquote ve to look here\rquote \'94. And there\rquote s this detailed interrogation of
 [the item]. One other thing I should say, the other kind of historical social science that I am tremendously impressed by, is historical demography, the kind of thing that Peter Laslett, whom I knew quite well in Cambridge, started off there, and I think
 that, again, has been tremendously important. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
