\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
Oh, well, the answer is a peculiar one. Entirely non-academic. As I mentioned to you before, I played a lot of tennis, and in those days \endash  this is late fifties/early sixties - tennis was, in principle, amateur - not professional like i
t is now. But there was a thing call \'93Shamateurism\'94 \endash  \'93Sham amateurism\'94 \endash 
 where, if you played at tournaments, you got hospitality, then you were given expenses on top, and if you won anything, you got these vouchers which you were supposed to use to buy a clock or something like that \endash 
 you would sell them back to the club after the tournament, to make a bit of money. Well, I wasn\rquote t good enough to be a shamateur in Britain, but I was just about good enough to be shamateur in Ireland. So there were quite a f
ew summers, when I was a student and junior lecturer and things, I would go off and play tennis in Ireland \endash  it amounted to a free holiday! And made a bit of money! Of course, I\rquote d read a lot about Ireland\rquote 
s history and I just did become fascinated with the
 society, sociologically, because when we went over there as shamateurs, we were put up in the grand houses of the Anglo-Irish, in towns like Mallow and so on. And then in the clubs, you got this fascinating mixture of the Anglo-Irish, and the rising Cath
olic professionals \endash  the \'85 the lawyers and the doctors and so on \endash  and it\rquote 
s a very interesting mix, I found it fascinating. And then what happened was, when I came to Nuffield, we had a very steady flow of very good Irish students, so I had a lot of Irish g
raduate students, and so we had then several meetings in Nuffield, between British and Irish sociologists, and out of that came the book that I edited with Chris Whelan, who was one of the leading Irish sociologists on the industrial development of Irelan
d
. Because it was a fascinating case of a society that became modern before it became industrial, and Tony Wrigley, who was in Oxford at that time, had a very good essay on the importance of not confusing modernisation with industrialisation, and Ireland w
as a wonderful example. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
