\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh! Well, perhaps it would be useful to do it with the example of social mobility \endash 
 that would make it a bit more concrete. Okay. Causal path analysis is a form of correlation and regression analysis, and to use it, you really need to work with continuous variables.
 So if you were wanting to study social mobility this way, you might, for example, take a scale of occupational prestige or status, and consider individuals on positions on this scale \endash  their destination positions, and then their fathers\rquote 
, or their parenta
l position on this scale - that would be the origins. And then you would measure social mobility, or immobility, simply by the correlation between the score of the father, on the occupational status scale, and the score of the child on the occupational st
a
tus scale. That would probably work out at something like 0.3-0.4. Okay. So then you might want to ask - well, what about variables that mediate between origin and destination, in terms of occupational status? And an obvious candidate here would be educat
ion. So you want to measure that in a continuous way, say years of completed education. Then, what causal path analysis would allow you to do, would be to decompose this overall correlation of, let\rquote s say about 0.3 or 0.4, into two parts \endash 
 one part that went through education, from origin to education, and then from education to destination; and the other part that didn\rquote t go through education, if you like \endash 
 the direct effect. And then, of course, you could elaborate on this. You could bring in a fourth and fi
fth variable. You might want to bring in IQ as measured in early life. You might want to bring in occupational status of the first occupation that the individuals had on entering the labour market. And path analysis will then allow you still finer decompo
sition of this overall association through all the paths that you might draw between these variables. So from that point of view, it can be quite revealing. However, it\rquote s got at least two big problems. One is it\rquote 
s a form of standardised regression, so really, you can\rquote t separate out the effects of the marginal distributions of all these variables from the effects of their net correlation. You can\rquote 
t take account, for example, of the fact that between the parents\rquote  generation and the child\rquote s generation, the shap
e of the occupational structure may have changed, or the distribution of education may have changed, and that becomes especially problematic when you may want to be comparing samples over long periods of time, or across countries. Second problem is that i
t\rquote s totally a linear system, and you have to assume that the results you come up with, just apply equally across the whole of the population that you\rquote re looking at. For example, you\rquote 
ve got to assume that the role of education in social mobility is the same wherever you start off and wherever you end up, and, in fact, we know that\rquote s not true. For example, if you\rquote 
re the son of a small proprietor, a lot of sons of small proprietors end up simply inheriting the family business, and education is of pretty negligible importance. On the other hand, if you\rquote 
re the son of a manual wage worker, and you end up as a salaried professional, you can be pretty sure education was crucial. So it assumes, path analysis, that the same regression rules apply across the board, and we know that\rquote 
s not true. Okay. Log-linear modelling again, thinking of it in terms of mobility analysis, here you\rquote re basically working with categorical variables, and you don\rquote t even have to assume that they\rquote re ordered, they\rquote 
re just different. So you could think, in this case, say, of social mobility, in terms of some kind of class schema. You might think of the classes as being ordered but for the purposes of analysis, that doesn\rquote 
t matter. So you have a mobility table which simply classifies individuals by their own class position as against their parents\rquote 
 class position. And what log-linear modelling then will enable you to do, is to look at the association between origins and destinations defined in this way, using what we call \'93odds ratios\'94. And in this c
ase you can very clearly separate out the effects of changes in the marginal distributions from any changes in the underlying association, net of the marginal distributions. And moreover, you can do this almost on a cell by cell basis, so you don\rquote 
t have to assume that the same patterns of association operate across the board. It\rquote s a much more disaggregated kind of analysis. So you can say, \'93
Yes, small proprietors, self-employed workers, have a much higher propensity for immobility than do, say, clerical workers - things of this kind. So it\rquote 
s very valuable when you want to look at changes in mobility over time, or across societies, because you can make then this crucial distinction between absolute mobility rates, which reflect the effects of changes in the m
arginal distributions, from relative mobility rates which just focus on the net associations. However, then there is a downside, and that is that it\rquote 
s much more difficult, taking this approach, to bring in intervening, mediating variables like education, and to distinguish the indirect and direct effects. Now, this is one of the big statistical issues at the moment \endash 
 how can you do the equivalent of causal path analysis in this context of discrete variables and non-linear models? And it\rquote s attracting a lot o
f attention at the moment, together with a statistician at LSE, Jouni Kuha, I got a paper in the Journal of the Royal Statistical Society a few years ago, which, I think, gives a theoretical solution to this problem, but it\rquote 
s not altogether practical once you work with more than three classes. We\rquote re still working on that in the context of our present project. Other people are coming up with somewhat similar/somewhat different solutions, so that\rquote 
s how it stands! (LAUGHS) I don\rquote t know whether that\rquote s very comprehensible to a non-statistician, but that\rquote s how it looks to a mobility researcher! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
