\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, we did include women, at a later stage \endash 
 and this is in the second edition of my book on Social Mobility and Class Structure in Modern Britain. By that time we could take more data from the British General Election Studies, to deal with women\rquote s mobility. And the short answer
 is that so far as inter-generational mobility is concerned, the patterns were essentially the same as for men, so none of the major conclusions from the first edition had to be changed. I mean, women, like men, across the cohorts we studied, had increasi
ng chances of upward mobility that was almost entirely due to the marginal effects, the changing shape of the class structure. There\rquote s more room at the top, so, like men, they moved up. They didn\rquote 
t enter the higher level professional and managerial position
s to the same extent, but still the clear pattern was for upward mobility - thinking in absolute terms. When you came to look at the relative rates then for women, just as for men, these were essentially stable across the cohorts, and there was no very gr
e
at difference in the degree of fluidity between men and women. If anything, women possibly showed greater fluidity, but that was very doubtful - really not much difference. So from the point of view of intergenerational mobility, no, the gender difference
s were very slight when you looked at the trends. In fact, now, in our current project, which is based on the British cohort studies, of course we can look at men and women, and now with some interest, it seems. We\rquote 
ve a paper under review which is a bit more interesting in terms of gender differences. What we\rquote re finding now is that among women fluidity has increased \endash  not among men \endash 
 and the interesting question is why that should be so? There are two competing [answers] that we can\rquote t decide between at the m
oment, but we will. One is that education-based meritocracy is more developed among women than among men. Women have been, as we know, have been doing better than men educationally, and it does seem that women\rquote 
s educational attainment is somewhat less closely linked to their social origins than men. It may be that something is happening - that education counts for more for women in where they end up, than for men. So that\rquote 
s one possible interpretation, that women\rquote s mobility is being more governed by a kind of education-based meritocracy. But there\rquote s another slightly less positive interpretation that what we\rquote 
re really seeing here is a kind of increase in \'93perverse\'94 fluidity, and this comes about from the fact that more women than previously are not leaving th
e labour market in the period of active motherhood, but are staying in, but on a part-time basis, and often accepting some kind of job downgrading. So that perhaps women from more advantaged backgrounds, who, themselves, started off their working lives in
 
managerial and professional positions - more of these women now are staying in the labour market, but being downwardly mobile in course of their own lives, and that then shows up in greater inter-generational fluidity. So both of these things could be tru
e to some extent, but that\rquote s what we\rquote re working on at the moment. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Presumably in, what we might call the \'93old days\'94 when women\rquote 
s own occupational mobility was not investigated, and they were simply classified by their husband\rquote s occupation \'85 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
