\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yeah. Well, I should say, at the start, that I\rquote m always very sceptical when people talk about \'93mixed methods\'94 as if it
\rquote s something, as it were, good in itself, without explaining why mixed methods might be thought to give an advantage. Although I primarily
 work in quantitative sociology because, I suppose, my overall conception of sociology is as a kind of population science, I mean, what we\rquote re really interested in is aggregate level regularities among human populations. I\rquote 
m inclined to work quantitatively because that\rquote s the way I think you have to deal with population aggregates. But I do think that there is a role for qualitative work in sociology, in at least one particular respect, and that is where you\rquote 
ve established, empirically, some population regularity which, for me, is the basic kind of explananda for sociology of established patterns of social mobility or patterns of formation and dissolution of partnerships, or whatever: we\rquote 
ve done that statistically, then you want to be able to explain why these regularities are as they are, or if they change, why they change, and you can\rquote t do that through statistics. You\rquote 
ve got to come up with some kind of social process or mechanism, and a level of social action and interaction that explains why, statistically,
 you can see these regularities, and once you come up with some theory - I mean, as in the genuine meaning of theory, I mean some explanatory model, something that tells you why something is as it is. Your next step, then, is to test that theory. Here, I 
t
hink there is a role for qualitative work, because there are basically two ways, I think, to test theoretical explanations of social regularities - explanations that are given in terms of social processes at the level of action . One is the kind of indire
ct test. You can say, \'93Well, if this mechanism that you propose is actually going on, then we ought to be able to see this, this, and this - other indications\'94
. And you may then want to do more statistical analyses to see if you find that. But the other way is more direct. We can say, \'93
Well, if this process is really going on in families, or in schools, or wherever - all causation, in one sense, is local causation - we ought to be able to get in there and see it actually happening\'94. And this is where, I beli
eve, there still is a role for serious ethnography, but it has to be serious ethnography, and I think that we lost that in sociology \endash  this kind of thing I call \lquote Blitzkrieg ethnography\'94
, where, you know, somebody just hangs around for a few days, and does nothing very much. We\rquote 
ve got to go back to the, if you like, the Malinowskian conception of ethnography, where people really did spend a long time in the field. Of course, that is difficult in modern societies. Because, for example, one area where Richard 
Breen and I developed an explanatory theory for some statistical regularities, was educational choice \endash  how the kids decide, together with their parents, what educational choices they\rquote 
re going to make. And you could, in principle, test this by ethnography. But then the trouble is, what\rquote s the locale? Because it\rquote 
s not like the tribal society where you can sit down under the banana tree and watch everything going on! (LAUGHS) Some of it goes on in the family, some of it goes on in the school, some of it goes on in peer groups, and it\rquote 
s not easy, then, to do detailed ethnographic work in, say, all three locales at the same time \endash  that\rquote s the problem. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Although I think wouldn\rquote t the anthropologists say, \'93Well, actually you can sit down und
er your banana tree, but your wife still had to go and talk to the women because you weren\rquote t allowed to\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
