\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Oh well, my favourite ethnographer is Martin Sanchez-Janowski, who\rquote s American, and he\rquote 
s done wonderful studies of American gangs. Islands in the Streets is a wonderful
 book! It took him 12 years, and, you know, several different gangs in different parts of America, and he really did spend a lot of time with these gangs, so it can be done. There was another book that we used, very influential when we did our work on cul
tural participation - dammit, I\rquote ve forgotten the name of it! A guy in New York who was very interested in the role that art, pictorial art, played in people\rquote s lives, and did a study \endash  in two areas of New York \endash 
 of the actual pictures that people had on thei
r apartment walls, and why they selected them, and what it meant to them. And again, you know, spent a very long time going to these houses, photographing what was on the walls, talking to them. So it can be done. There are examples of this. And in this c
ountry, there\rquote s one - a man called Dick Hobbs. I read some [of his] ethnographic work, which I thought was fascinating. And in this College, we have [as one of our] \'93specialities\'94 now, a study of Mafias, and in part, that\rquote 
s done by a detailed ethnography. T
hey use other material [too. There was] a wonderful seminar just this week on how Mafia gangs can have credible commitments, given the general low trust context, and this was all based on analysis of transcripts of conversations that the police made - I m
ean, unknown to the Mafia - and these guys have got hold of these transcripts and they\rquote ve done content analysis of them. But that is backed up by a lot of ethnographic work. I have to say it sounds pretty dangerous. (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
