\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Interesting! I don\rquote t know what I read, quite a few years ago, and I thought, \'93Well, this is the kind of thing\'94
. But this is where, you see, I think qualitative work, for me, is important if you really want to get down to the causal processes or mechanisms that underlie more general regularities. How do people really make choices about children\rquote 
s education? How do people really make choices about employment? I mean, in the States, you had Granovetter\rquote s work, which was very influential. What I have to say I\rquote 
m very critical of, is this kind of qualitative sociology that seems very prevalent in Britain now. If you open Sociology or Sociological Review, it\rquote s full of it - where people are studying a small group, it\rquote s usually called a \'93sample\'94
, but it\rquote s very unclear exactly what it\rquote s a sample of. And then you have, again, what are called \'93intensive interviews\'94, but often, it seems to me, they\rquote 
re no more intensive than you would do in a standard social survey. And then you get the results written up, and the general arguments are just illustrated with little snippets from the interviews. And I have to say I think this is la
rgely worthless because I always want to say, \'93But how representative?\'94 And, \'93Why did you pick that, rather than that?\'94
 And what makes it then worse is that, often, these data are not deposited in the archive. I did check some years ago with the Qualidata 
Archive, because I noticed that in the ESRC Regulations, whether you do quantitative or qualitative work, you should deposit the results in the Archive. So I asked what proportion of these qualitative studies deposited results in the Archive? And I was to
ld that that question couldn\rquote t be answered, because they didn\rquote t know how many grants had been made \endash  which seems very lax on somebody\rquote 
s part. And I did actually enquire about one or two studies, and I was told, no, nothing had been deposited. Now, I don\rquote t know what sanctions ESRC took in that regard, but I suspect none. So what I do feel very strongly about here is that there
\rquote s double standards operating. If I do a piece of quantitative research, I know I have to put the data in a clean, publicly accessible form in the Data Archive, and that\rquote 
s exactly as it should be, because it means, then, that this is the way in which social science is made public. Anybody who wants to check my results, it\rquote s open to them to do it. They can get exactly the data set I used, 
with recording scheme and everything. Well, with one exception we now have, which we were just talking about today, this 1946 birth cohort which is still run by the Medical Research Council, and they have a different ethic, and they won\rquote 
t put that in the public domain. And I\rquote m getting very angry with them, because I said, \'93I made it a point that every piece of quantitative research I do, anybody can check with the data in the public domain\'94. I don\rquote t like it, that that
\rquote s not in fact the case. You can get it, but you\rquote ve to go through a whole series of ridiculous hoops to do so. But I really do think \endash  coming back to qualitative research \endash  that this should be enforced, that people \'85
 I mean, there are, now \endash  as you probably know \endash  all these computer programmes like NUDIST and others that do enable you to put your qualitative data into a publicly accessible form. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I\rquote m no expert in this, but I\rquote m fairly certain one of the huge difficulties is adequately anonymising the data. You can
\rquote t anonymise it nearly as easily. You can\rquote t put your clean survey data set, it\rquote s hard work, but it can be cleaned, and very carefully anonymised, and that\rquote s available for anybody to look at\'85 It is very difficult if you
\rquote ve got qualitative materials\'85 You can obviously go through some field notes, or ethnographer\rquote s fieldwork diary, you can obviously go through transcripts of audio recorded interviews, keep the video out \endash  that\rquote 
s a bit more of a problem. But if you then go through them and take out all the identifying details, questions arise as to whether or not you\rquote 
re going to be losing some of the very material, some of the data, and in which case, how do you stop that. I\rquote m not saying that that explains why so few were deposited, but I\rquote m saying that is quite a big discussion, and quite a big hurdle
\'85. It\rquote s the interviewer\rquote s anonymity and confidentiality at stake as well as the researcher\rquote s. But I think they\rquote 
re thinking about that in terms of interviews, whereas you and I, I think, are also talking about ethnography, not merely qualitative interviews. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
You see, there is a problem, on the question of anonymity. I would need a lot of convincing that this makes it impossible: even if you had to take one or two things out, as long as you indicated that something had been taken out here.
 But, look, turn it the other way around, if you can\rquote t put these data into the public domain, then in what sense can this be social science? I mean, how can one check on this? I don\rquote 
t try to impute any sort of deliberately misleading intentions to people d
oing qualitative research, but still I find the snippets that I read from interviews - well, yes, I can imagine some people said that, but the implication is that this was somehow a dominant or typical thing. I want to know, \'93
Surely some other people said very different things to that\'94, and I would like to go and look at the full record. And how can this be science, which is, essentially, a public activity, if the basic data are not shared? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 But it\rquote s interesting, because one of the things I thought you were going to say, when you were talking about what \endash 
 and I\rquote m putting this word into your mouth - \'93a degenerate version of qualitative research\'94 with the snippets, I thought you were going to say the data are then interpreted as if they\rquote re quantitative 
data, and the conclusions stand as though they\rquote re quantitative conclusions, because people say, \'93most\'94, \'93many\'94, and those are the quantitative, not qualitative [terms]. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yes. Well I could indeed have said that, because I do belie
ve that. Although this is called qualitative research, often when I read the arguments and the conclusions, it looks, to me, like quantitative research but without the numbers! (LAUGHS) So, yeah, again, they have to be clear about what\rquote 
s going on here. This is one reason why I think that qualitative research, for me, could be particularly important where you want to test some causal process that\rquote 
s been hypothesised - because I would love to be able to read the interviews, say, between parents and kids, when they are talking about whether the children should, say, at 16 stay on and do \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels, or go and get some technical qualification, or go into the labour market. Now, we\rquote d love to know what it actually sounds like \endash  what do they say? How is this discuss
ed? And, of course, it may be discussed in peer group, school, and so on. I think, in modern societies, ethnography is much more difficult than in simpler, more compact/less differentiated societies \endash  I\rquote m not saying it\rquote 
s easy there - but, yeah, you\rquote re right, this is a process that could go on over years, and in different locales and so on. Of course, that\rquote 
s what makes some people think the indirect way of testing these explanation is, in general, better, because it\rquote s very difficult to get right in there, on
 the ground, where these decisions are being made. Another thing about this is related: I do think qualitative researchers have to take much more seriously than they do, the methodology, and the rationale for the methodology. I mean, look at this way. If 
I go and look at various textbooks - I\rquote ve actually done this in the library here - on standard techniques for quantitative research \endash  regression, log-linear modelling, things like content analysis and so on \endash 
 okay, different textbooks have different emphases, different focuses, but basically they\rquote re telling the same story \endash  \'93this is how you do it\'94. When I look at textbooks on qualitative methods, I mean, they\rquote 
re all over the place. They\rquote re talking about completely different approaches, different themes. What
 is the canon? Is there a methodological canon or not? (LAUGHS) I would hate to be a graduate student doing qualitative work, because you wonder if they went from this university to that university, they would probably find it was totally different. But i
f I have somebody, who comes from University X or Y, and they\rquote re doing log-linear modelling of contingency tables, they\rquote re doing the same thing! (LAUGHS) So it is a problem! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 [Could we move] to Paul\rquote s question of your opinion of Glen Elder\rquote s development, developmental life course research, that
\rquote s based on mixed data from longitudinal studies. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
