\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 (LAUGHS) Expecting you to be a polymath! Well, that leads on to this last question \'85 He\rquote 
s actually assuming there is failure of British sociology in this connection. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, I would agree. I think, over the last 20 years or so, there has been an increasing failure of British sociolo
gy to have the kind of impact on public discussion of policy issues, and in the actual process of policy formation, and I\rquote 
m afraid I do have to relate it to the very weak position of quantitative sociology in Britain, and the dominance of qualitative approaches. The last 10 or 15 years I\rquote 
ve been involved with a range of government departments and agencies and QUANGOS, and it seemed pretty clear to me that what they want is strong quantitative data - you know, that really relates to the British population at
 large, or to well-defined sections of it, and they want cogent analysis. The difficulty that I found has been remarkable \endash  I\rquote ve been told there\rquote 
s several different places where they cannot recruit sociologists with the necessary technical skills to do the kind of work that they want. With the result that I\rquote 
ve seen this in the Cabinet Office, Department of Business Innovation and Skills, and in what used to be the Departments of Carpets and Soft Furnishings as we called it! Communities, Schools and Families
, now Department of Education. The civil servants I work with there, have not been trained in sociology. They\rquote 
re predominantly economists, but then with some other people from geography, psychology, but all with a good training in survey research and quantitative data analysis - and for better or for worse, that\rquote s what government departments want. And I
\rquote m afraid that British sociology departments are not providing them with that. Nor, I think, are many people, doing sociological research. What is really str
ange is that this should happen at a time when more and more of the central problems that are coming up in the public policy field, are more sociological than economic. (LAUGHS) I mean, all this stuff on social mobility, all the stuff on immigration, crim
e, and so on \endash  well, I think crime\rquote s a bit different, we have one or two good criminology departments and criminologists - but it\rquote 
s a worry. And particularly the takeover by the economists, because they are highly organised, they do look after each other, and it\rquote 
s amazing the number of issues in public policy field, where the economists are really taking over, and where sociologists are very poorly represented. I\rquote ve seen it with this - you know, I\rquote 
ve been in this battle for the last ten years now, with the economists, over social mobility - their interpretation and our interpretation. But I am very much aware that I don\rquote t have very many comrades on the side of sociology. We\rquote 
ve got this little group that we\rquote ve built up here. But you look around, and there\rquote s not much else going on. And it\rquote s the same with problems of ethnicity. And I\rquote 
ve a nasty feeling that unless British sociology gets its act together, it will become marginalised in the next five or ten years, and it will be the economists who have taken over. I mean, it\rquote 
s no good - you get people, somebody like David Byrne at Durham, and other places, railing on about economists, and how it\rquote s all nonsense and so on and so forth \endash  that will get us nowhere. We\rquote 
ve got to be in the same research fields, doing research of similar rigour to the research they do, but challenging their assumptions, and their analyses, and their conclusions. And unless we do that, I think the outlook is very grim. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Interesting you\rquote ve developed your discussion of Paul\rquote s question in that direction, because I was wondering \'85
 if you saw a parallel role now, for sociology that could be developed, or is being developed, or is failing to be developed? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Yeah. Well, I see there is a slightly different question, and what I don\rquote t think is helpful - to begin by negative \endash 
 is this idea of the sociologist as public intellectuals. I don\rquote t like the concept of public intellectual very much at all, because it seems to me to be inflated. I mean, these are often people who are sort of sounding o
ff about topics that they really don\rquote t have any detailed knowledge of. If you take an example, you look at all the stuff that Tony Giddens did on the \'93third way\'94, I don\rquote 
t think that was very helpful either from the point of view of politics or social science. Or again, the stuff that Manuel Castells did. I have written about this elsewhere, but I don\rquote t think that is very helpful. I think it\rquote 
s important that sociologists are ready to take up public positions in regard to political as well as to policy issues
: but then, if we want to do that, we have to do it as sociologists, on the basis of the particular kinds of knowledge that we know how to produce. I think that\rquote 
s the kind of basis. So if we want to be effective in the public realm as political actors, I think, first and foremost, we\rquote 
ve to be good as social scientists. And so in a sense these two things do come back together again. One of the difficulties we have, incidentally, in this regard, is the appalling understanding of sociology in the press and the
 media generally. I mean, most of the people who write on social issues, really haven\rquote t much of a clue. Apart from anything else, they tend to be innumerate. You know, I have a lot of time for Polly Toynbee, I\rquote 
m very sympathetic to her general stance on things. But I\rquote ve had discussions with her from time to time, and it is very difficult, because she does find it hard to grasp anything with a quantitative element, and she\rquote 
s not the only one. You see, there, the economists are much better served than we are, because you do have these economic correspondents, financial correspondents, who do have a professional background in the subject. They\rquote 
ve degrees, sometimes higher degrees. You get somebody like Sam Brittain, well, he\rquote s almost retired now, first rate training as an economist, and yet Sam could push \endash  I mean, I often didn\rquote 
t agree with Sam and what he was doing, but he was very good at it, in linking the professional world of economics, with the public world. And we don\rquote t have that equivalent for sociology. I\rquote 
ve got a little list - when we publish anything, we go through the Press Office here - but the number of people you can rely on, in the media, not to completely garble what you\rquote re saying \endash  have some understanding of it \endash 
 is very small. Even if they\rquote ve got the best will in the world it is a problem. We\rquote 
ve talked a lot about it with our Press Office here, and we put a lot of effort into writing press releases to try and make it as clear as possible, but then when you see what comes out (LAUGHS) Oh! So I th
ink this is a bit of a problem that we have with the media. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 I hope I haven\rquote t worn you out with all these question! I think one thing, if there\rquote 
s anything on reflection that comes to you, that you were going to say, is there anything you\rquote d like to add? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 No, I don\rquote t think so. I mean, perhaps just one thing, but it may well have come out, anyway, in what\rquote 
s gone, but I do, generally, looking back over my career, feel pretty sad about the way in which British sociology has gone over the last 20 or
 30 years. Because I think, compared, you know, with the kind of sociology that I see being done, in particular, elsewhere in Europe, through these EU networks that I\rquote 
ve been involved in, through the European Consortium for Social Research, I do feel we are way way behind. And I sometimes wonder if I shouldn\rquote t have done more to try and offset that in some way. But, you know, for many years now, I\rquote 
ve felt completely isolated in British sociology outside Oxford, and it seemed pretty futile to try and do anything. I mean, one really remarkable thing was that the book that I published on sociology wasn\rquote 
t reviewed in Sociology or in Sociological Review It was reviewed in the BJS, but, you know, it was reviewed in all the other leading sociological journals in Eur
ope, and America. BBut the BSA decided that they would ignore it. I feel that the situation is very sad in Britain, and especially when you see what\rquote 
s happening elsewhere in Europe, because I think I said, when we talked last time, that the most rewarding thing that\rquote 
s happened in my career in the last ten years, is seeing the quality of work that young people are now doing at these conferences that I\rquote ve been to. And the staggering thing is, virtually no Brits there, and that is very disturbing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par Anne:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 Well, that\rquote s going to take a huge amount of analysis and discussion! I think formally and officially, I\rquote 
m going to thank you once again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 
\par 
\par John:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10491433\charrsid10491433 That\rquote s alright. Fine. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1772273 
